# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 100-meter-running-deer
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-deer] 1908 was the first time of running deer at the Olympics, and the target was specified to placed at 110 yards (100.584 meters) and made 10 runs of 75 feet (23 meters) for about 4 seconds each.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-deer] The deer target had a scoring area of three concentric circles, with the smallest counting for 4 points, the middle for 3, and the outermost for 2.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-deer] A hit outside the circles but still on the target (except on the haunch) counted for 1 point.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-deer] The target made 10 runs for each shooter both in the Single- and Double-Shot event, and in the Team event each team consisted of four shooters.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-deer] Thus the individual double-shot event a maximum of 80 points per shooter, the Individual Single-Shot event had a maximum 40 points per shooter, and the Team Single-Shot event had a maximum of (4·40 =) 160 points per team.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-deer] In the 1912 event the target had been changed to have 5 scoring areas, with 5 point for inner scoring area.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-deer] The target distance was now specified as 100 meters.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-deer] Each shooter still got 10 runs, and thus the maximum possible points thus became maximum 100 points for Individual Double-Shot, 50 for Individual Single-Shot and 200 for Team Single-Shot respectively.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-deer] 20 shooters from 6 nations competed in the Individual Double-Shot event, 20 shooters from 5 nations competed in the Team Single-Shot event, and 34 sport shooters from 7 nations competed in the Team Single-Shot event.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-deer] In 1920 the events were held on 27 July.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-deer] 8 shooters from 3 nations competed in the Individual Double-Shot event, while 12 shooters from 4 nations competed in the Individual Single-Shot event.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-deer] This championship saw the introduction of the Team Double-Shot event, now in addition to the Team Single-Shot event.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-deer] 20 shooters from four nations competed in both these events.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-deer] In 1924 the events were held from 30 June to 3 July at the shooting range in Le Stand de Tir de Versailles in Versailles, France.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-deer] The number, types and format of the events was similar as in the 1920 Olympics.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-deer] First out was the Individual Single-Shot event in 30 June where 32 shooters from 8 nations competed.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-deer] The day after on 1 July the Individual Double-Shot event was held, with 31 shooters from 8 nations.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-deer] The last two days consisted of the Team events.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-deer] Team Single-Shot was held on 2 July with 25 shooters from 7 nations.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-deer] Notably, Czechoslovakia was allowed to compete with an incomplete team; only one shooter participated.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-deer] Lastly the Team Double-Shot event was held on 3 July, with 25 shooters from 7 nations.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-deer] Notably Hungary was allowed to compete with an incomplete team; only one shooter participated.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-deer] Running deer events would not be held again at the Olympics until 1952, meaning that the event was not included in the 1928, 1932, 1936 and 1948 Summer Olympics.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-deer] 1924 would also be the last time of format with separate Single- and Double-Shot events, as well as any Team events.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-deer] In the 1952 Olympics in Helsinki, Finland, running deer was again on the Olympic program, but this time in the new format of the Individual Combined Single- and Double-Shot event only.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-deer] The competition was held on 28 and 29 July, and 14 shooters from 7 nations competed.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-deer] The winner, John Larsen from Norway, scored 413 points.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-deer] In the 1956 Summer Olympics in Melbourne, Australia was again arranged in the format of an Individual Combined Single- and Double-Shot event on 3 and 4 December.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-deer] The winner, Vitali Romanenko from Ukrainia and competing for the Soviet Union, scored 441 points.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-deer] This was the last time running deer was arranged as a part of the Olympics.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-moose] The sport is popular in Norway, Sweden and Finland, with competitions being arranged by the Norwegian Association of Hunters and Anglers, Svenska Jägareförbundet and Finnish Hunters' Association, respectively.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-moose] Events are most commonly shot at 100 meters, but sometimes 80 meters instead (particularly in Sweden).
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-moose] The use of electronic targets is common, but cardboard targets are also sometimes used.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-moose] In the 1950s, many shooting ranges in Norway had already been set up for training on running moose targets, but it was first introduced as a competition in the 1960s by the Norwegian Association of Hunters and Anglers.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-moose] Interest increased steadily, and in the 1980s over 130 shooting ranges across Norway were set up for running moose.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-moose] In Hordaland and Sogn og Fjordane in Western Norway, it was for long common to change the running moose targets with one of a running deer with the same hit zones and points, since there is little moose and a lot of red deer in those regions.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-moose] Nowadays, most ranges have changed to standard moose targets.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-moose] The first 10 rounds are shot at a static target, while the last 10 rounds are fired at a moving target.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-moose] Both the static and running target have an inner hit zone, denoted with a star (*), used to distinguish the best shooters.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-moose] The 5 first rounds at the static target are fired from a seated position, which is to be completed during a 2 minute string.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-moose] The next 5 rounds are fired at the same target, but from a standing position, also within a 2 minute string.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-moose] The static target stage has available a maximum of 50 points with 10 inside hits, called "50-10", and this forms a basis before the running target shooting event.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-moose] The moving target string consists of 10 rounds.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-moose] The target moves sideways with a velocity of approximately 5 m/s (18 km/h; 11 mph), appearing from cover and disappearing after each pass.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-moose] The target can only be engaged with one round for each of its ten passes.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-moose] With the visible opening being around 20-25 meters wide, this means that the moose is visible for around 4-5 seconds during each pass.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-moose] The moving target stage has available a maximum of 50 points with 10 inside hits, called "50-10".
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-moose] The combined maximum points for a match is 100 points with 20 inside hits, called "100-20".
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-moose] Competitors are divided into several classes based on equipment, age and previous accomplishments.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-moose] In the Nordic championships, there is only one equipment class, and competitors are divided into the classes *senior*, *D2*, *E1*, *E2* and *F*.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-moose] Here the minimum bullet diameter is 6.5 mm (i.e.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-moose] 6.5x55 mm or 6.5x47 mm), the minimum trigger pull is 1 kg, and the rifle can weigh maximum 5.5 kg.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-moose] The sporter class has no maximum weight for the rifle, and it is common to use heavy "sporter rifles".
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-moose] The smallest permitted cartridge is .222 Rem (since 1 January 2015, formerly the minimum bullet diameter was 6.5 mm).
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-moose] Some of the most commonly seen cartridges in competitions are .223 Remington, 6.5×55 mm, .308 Win and .30-06.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-moose] Scopes can be chosen freely, regardless of magnification.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-moose] The hunter class (*jegerklassen*) was originally aimed at typical hunting rifle setups, but today most compete with special built competition rifles.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-moose] There is a maximum weight of 5 kg for the rifle, and scope sights can have a 12x maximum magnification.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-moose] As with the sporter class, the minimum trigger pull is 1 kg, and the smallest permitted cartridge i .222 Rem.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-moose] The cartridges most commonly seen in competitions are the same as for the sporter class.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-moose] Younger junior (*yngre junior*) permits any cartridge, and it is common to see participants shooting .22 LR, .223 Remington, 6.5×55 mm, .308 Win or .30-06.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-moose] As for the other classes, the minimum trigger pull weight is 1 kg.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/100-meter-running-moose] There is no weight limit on the firearm, and scope sights can be chosen freely.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] The **1908 Summer Olympics** (officially the **Games of the IV Olympiad** and also known as **London 1908**) were an international multi-sport event held in London, England, from 27 April to 31 October 1908.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] The 1908 Games were relocated to London after Italy withdrew from hosting on financial grounds.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] Archival research has established that the British Olympic Association was already privately exploring the possibility of London hosting the Games as early as 5 January 1906, three months before the eruption began.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] London was formally confirmed as host on 19 November 1906.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] Rome eventually hosted the Games in 1960.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] These were the fourth chronological modern Summer Olympics in keeping with the now-accepted four-year cycle as opposed to the alternate four-year cycle of the proposed Intercalated Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] The IOC president for these Games was Baron Pierre de Coubertin.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] Lasting a total of 187 days (six months and four days), these were the longest Games in modern Olympics history.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] There were four bids for the 1908 Summer Olympics.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] Rome was selected ahead of London, Berlin and Milan.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] The selection was made at the 6th IOC Session in London in 1904.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] Italian authorities were preparing to stage the games when Mount Vesuvius erupted on 7 April 1906, devastating the city of Naples.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] Funds were diverted to the reconstruction of Naples, so a new host country was required.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] During the Intercalated Games of Athens, still in April 1906, Coubertin approached Lord Desborough about alternatively hosting in London.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] Accepting the offer and with a mere 18 months in which to prepare, London was selected for the first time to hold the Games, which were held at White City alongside the Franco-British Exhibition, at the time the more noteworthy event.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] The White City Stadium, built in short time for the Games, held 68,000 people, with full crowds turning up to watch the events.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] The stadium track was three laps to the mile (536.448 metres per lap), as the current standard of 400 metres did not exist until 1962, with a pool (for swimming and diving events) and platforms (for wrestling and gymnastics) in the centre field.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] On the opening day, following the practice introduced at the Intercalated Games of 1906, teams paraded behind national flags.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] The 1908 Olympics also prompted establishment of standard rules for sports, and selection of judges from different countries rather than just the host.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] One reason was the 400 metre race, in which a US runner, John Carpenter, was accused by the British officials of interfering with a British runner.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] Part of the problem was the different definition of interference under British and international rules (the events were held under British rules by the decision of the Organising Committee).
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] The officials decided to disqualify Carpenter and ordered a second final race without him.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] British Halswelle was to face the other two finalists.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] These athletes, William Robbins and John Taylor, were both Americans and decided not to participate in the repeat of the final to protest against the judges' decision.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] Halswelle was thus the only medallist in the 400 metres.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] The most famous incident of the games came at the end of the marathon.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] Dorando Pietri, Italy, began his race at a rather slow pace, but in the second half of the course began a powerful surge moving him into second position by the 32 km (20 mi) mark, 4 minutes behind South African Charles Hefferon.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] When he knew that Hefferon was in crisis, Pietri further increased his pace, overtaking him at the 39 km (24 mi) mark.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] The effort took its toll and with only two kilometres to go, Pietri began to feel the effects of extreme fatigue and dehydration.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] When he entered the stadium, he took the wrong path and when umpires redirected him, he fell down for the first time.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] He got up with their help, in front of 75,000 spectators.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] He fell four more times, and each time the umpires helped him up.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] In the end, though totally exhausted, he managed to finish the race in first place.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] Of his total time of 2h 54min 46s, ten minutes were needed for that last 340 metres.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] The American team immediately lodged a complaint against the help Pietri received from the umpires.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] The complaint was accepted and Pietri was disqualified and removed from the final standings of the race.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] Since he had not been responsible for his disqualification, Queen Alexandra awarded him a gilded silver cup the next day.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] These Games were the first to include winter events, as had originally been proposed for the Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] There were four figure skating events, although held on 28 and 29 October, months after most of the other events.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] Oscar Swahn from Sweden, who won the gold medal for running deer shooting, became the oldest Olympic champion of all time, and set another age record by being 72 years and 279 days old during his triumph at the 1920 Summer Olympics in Antwerp, Belgium.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] One of the more unusual shooting events in 1908 was Olympic dueling.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] The discipline, which was an associate event (that is, not official), was performed by facing opponents wearing protective clothing and masks and firing wax bullets.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] American John Taylor was a member of the winning medley relay team, making him the first African-American athlete to win an Olympic gold medal.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] Times for the winning team were United States (3:29.4): William Hamilton, 200 metres (22.0); Nathaniel Cartmell, 200 metres (22.2); John Taylor, 400 metres (49.8); and Melvin Sheppard, 800 metres (1:55.4).
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] Less than five months after returning from the Olympic Games in London, Taylor died of typhoid fever on 2 December 1908 at the age of 26.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] The budget of the organising committee showed a cost of £15,000; over one-third was labelled "entertainment expense".
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] Donations were the major source of revenue; only 28% of income derived from ticket sales.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] Total receipts of £21,378 resulted in organisers claiming a profit.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] Construction of the White City Stadium, which cost the government about £60,000, was not counted.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] Twenty-two sports, representing 110 events in 25 sporting disciplines, were competed.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] A golf tournament had also been planned but it was cancelled a few days before it was scheduled to start.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] Swimming, diving, and water polo are considered three disciplines of the same sport, *aquatics*.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] At the time, tug-of-war was part of athletics and the two different football codes (association and rugby (union)) were listed together.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee now considers tug-of-war a separate sport as well as referring to association football as simply "football" and to rugby union as "rugby." In one of seven cycling events (cycling sprint) no medals were awarded.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] The sailing program was open for a total of five sailing classes, but actually only four sailing events were competed.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] The number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] Cycle polo, glima and pistol dueling were demonstration sports.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] Thirteen sports venues were used for the 1908 Summer Olympics.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] The first winter sports took place at Prince's Skating Club in Knightsbridge.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] White City Stadium served as a precursor to modern stadiums.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] The figure skating events were not held at the next Olympics in Stockholm, but returned for the 1920 Games in Antwerp, heralding the first Winter Olympics that took place in Chamonix in 1924.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] White City was the main venue for the 1934 British Empire Games (known as the Commonwealth Games since 1978) and, before its demolition in 1985, also served as a venue for the 1966 FIFA World Cup.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] The All England Lawn Tennis Club continues to host the Wimbledon championships and is the only venue of the 1908 Games that was used for the 2012 Summer Olympics.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] Bisley and Henley served as venues in the 1948 Games when the Olympics returned to London forty years later.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] The 1908 Games featured athletes representing 22 National Olympic Committees.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] Finland, Turkey and New Zealand (as part of the team from Australasia) made their first appearance at the Olympic Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] The fact that the United Kingdom competed as a single team was upsetting to some Irish competitors, who felt that Ireland should compete on its own, despite being part of the UK at the time.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] They relied on the precedent set by Grand Duchy of Finland, which while being a part of the Russian Empire, competed in London as a separate country.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] Fearing an Irish boycott, the authorities changed the name of the team to Great Britain/Ireland, and in two sports, field hockey and polo, Ireland participated as a separate country, winning silver medals in both, although their medals counted towards the UK's tally.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] Irish athletes in the United States were not affected by this controversy, and many Irish immigrants to the United States competed for the U.S.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] Olympic team as members of the Irish American Athletic Club.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] Members of the Irish American Athletic Club won ten of the U.S.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] Olympic team's total 23 gold medals, or as many as the nations of France, Germany and Italy combined.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] Britain had more than a quarter of competitors in their team, with 676, compared to 112 on the American team which placed second in the medal standings.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1908-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1908 Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The **1912 Summer Olympics** (Swedish: *Olympiska sommarspelen 1912*), officially known as the **Games of the V Olympiad** (Swedish: *Den V olympiadens spel*) and commonly known as **Stockholm 1912**, were an international multi-sport event held in Stockholm, Sweden, between 6 July and 22 July 1912.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony was held on 6 July.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] They were the only Summer Olympics to be held in the 1910s as the 1916 Summer Olympics in Berlin were cancelled due to World War I.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Twenty-eight nations and 2,408 competitors, including 48 women, competed in 102 events in 14 sports.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] With the exception of tennis (starting on 5 May) and football and shooting (both starting on 29 June), the games were held within a month with an official opening on 6 July.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] It was the last Olympics to issue solid gold medals and, with Japan's debut, the first time an official team from an Asian nation participated.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Stockholm was the only bid for the games, and was selected in 1909.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The games were the first to have art competitions, women's diving, women's swimming, and the first to feature both the decathlon and the new pentathlon, both won by the American Jim Thorpe.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Electric timing was introduced in athletics, while the host country disallowed boxing.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Figure skating was rejected by the organizers because they wanted to promote the Nordic Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold medals (26), while hosts Sweden won the most medals overall (65).
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] These were the final Olympic Games for eight years due to the disruption of the First World War.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The next Olympic Games were held in 1920 in Antwerp.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Following the 1908 Summer Olympics in London, authorities in Sweden immediately sought to ensure that the next games would be held there.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] There were two Swedish members of the International Olympic Committee (IOC) at the time, Viktor Balck and Clarence von Rosen.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The pair proposed the idea to the Swedish governing bodies of athletics and gymnastics in order to ensure that they backed any potential bid.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Support was given by the national associations on 18 April 1909 for a bid to host the Olympics in Stockholm on the basis that suitable financial arrangements could be made.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] King Gustaf V was petitioned on 6 May 1909 following the publication of preliminary plans for the Stockholm bid that the expected cost of hosting the Games would be 415,000 kronor (£23,050 or $115,250).
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The Government accepted the petition on behalf of the King and supported the bid.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] On 28 May, at the meeting of the IOC in Berlin, the Swedish representatives declared that they had full financial support for hosting the next Games in Stockholm.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] A deal was made with the German IOC representative on the basis that Berlin would host the 1916 Summer Olympics.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Pierre de Coubertin spoke at the meeting about his concerns that Sweden should ensure that the Games take place, as he did not want a repeat of the problems with Great Britain hosting the 1908 Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The news that Stockholm was to host the 1912 Olympics was received with enthusiasm by the Swedish public.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The organizing committee took de Coubertin's words to heart, and aimed to achieve an Olympic Games which removed those elements which detracted from earlier Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The committee was elected in the autumn of 1909, with Balck voted as the President of the committee, and Crown Prince Gustaf Adolf selected as Honorary President.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The committee's first meeting took place on 7 October, and on 11 October they delegated the arrangements for the individual branches of sports to the relevant governing bodies in Sweden.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] There were four exceptions to this, with the game shooting, modern pentathlon and mountain ascents retained by the Olympic committee, and the horse riding competitions being organized by Prince Carl, Duke of Västergötland, who was the inspector of the Swedish cavalry.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Altogether there were 187 members of these committees.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The official invitation to compete in the Games was issued on 18 November 1910 to 27 countries, either directly or through their representative on the IOC.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] A further 15 countries were to have been invited, but as they had no IOC representatives, the Swedish authorities were unsure how to proceed.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Once the organizing committee for the Games received confirmation of the athletic associations in each of the 15 countries, they too were sent invitations.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Some 61,800 entry forms were printed for the use of the various nations.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Free transport was arranged for the invited nations' equipment, and a discount of 50 percent was arranged for competitors and delegates on the state run railway.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] A daily newspaper which only covered the Olympics was arranged to be published during the Games, in both English and Swedish.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Further arrangements were made for the general arrival of visitors in order to entertain them whilst they were not at the Games; a pleasure garden was opened north of the Olympic Stadium, and a series of indoor tennis courts were converted into a restaurant.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Twelve sports venues were used in the 1912 Summer Olympics.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] This marked the first time that more than one venue would be used for the football tournament, which has been the case ever since.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Stockholm Olympic Stadium served as one of the equestrian venues for the 1956 Summer Olympics.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Råsunda Stadium served as a venue for the 1958 FIFA World Cup and the 1995 FIFA Women's World Cup.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] In the initial bid document it was identified that a new stadium would be needed, initially envisaged as being located in the Östermalm Athletic Grounds.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] In order to save funds, it was expected that only one of the stadium's stands would be permanent, with the other three made of wood and dismantled following the Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The cost of that stadium was estimated at 235,000 Kronor.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Arrangements were made with the individual national committees to provide the use of Östermalm Athletic Grounds and Traneberg.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The cycling road race was held around Mälaren, the third largest lake in Sweden.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The water events, including the swimming and the rowing, were held at Djurgårdsbrunnsviken, where a stadium was built.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Kaknäs was already used as a shooting range, but alterations were needed to accommodate shooting events.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Although it was not used as the Olympic stadium as originally intended, Östermalm hosted the lawn tennis and fencing competitions after a tennis pavilion was moved there from another location.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Five other locations were considered in addition to the Östermalm Athletic Grounds to locate the Olympic Stadium.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The Stockholm Olympic Stadium was built on the site of the former Stockholm Athletic Grounds in order to retain the other locations for other uses during the Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] By placing it to the north of the city, the Olympic Stadium was within the immediate vicinity of other pre-existing sporting venues.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Initial funding was given to the sum of 400,000 Kr for a timber stadium but Torben Grut, the architect, also drew up alternative plans for a stone stadium.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] However it was found that the original estimate for the stone stadium would still be too expensive, and the plans were once more modified in order to simplify the design and reduce costs.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] An agreement was entered into with a contractor on 2 November 1910 that it would be transferred complete by 25 May 1912.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The Games of the V Olympiad were opened on 6 July 1912.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The Swedish Royal Family left Stockholm Palace at 10:40am, and were received at the Olympic Stadium by members of the IOC.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Three thousand competing athletes had already assembled in the nearby Östermalm Athletic Grounds, and began to enter the stadium in alphabetical order by nation according to the Swedish spelling.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The Swedish team entered last, but unlike the later tradition, the Greek team did not enter first.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] A hymn was sung, a traditional Swedish chant was conducted and prayers were read first in Swedish and then in English.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Crown Prince Gustaf Adolf addressed the King on behalf of the Swedish Olympic Association.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Afterwards a trumpet fanfare was played and the Crown Prince called for cheers for the King.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The athletes in their national groups marching out of the stadium in order ended the ceremony.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The Swedish delegation at the IOC meeting in Berlin on 28 May 1909 had proposed a simple Olympic schedule containing only "pure" athletics, swimming, gymnastics and wrestling.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] However other countries requested that the schedule be more comprehensive, and with that in mind they put forward a further programme at the IOC meeting in 1911 which was met with approval.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The sports which were added were the tug of war, cycling, fencing, football, horse riding, lawn tennis, rowing, shooting, skating and yacht racing.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The question of adding skating to the programme was discussed once more on 7 February 1910, with the decision being made to drop it from the schedule.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] It was felt to be unsuitable because it was a winter sport, and it was to be part of the Nordic Games the following year.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Boxing was removed from the programme as it was unappealing to the Swedes.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Art competitions were considered at a further meeting on 14 February 1910, and were subsequently added to the programme, but now art competitions are no longer regarded as official Olympic events by the International Olympic Committee.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] As a result, now the 1912 Summer Olympics programme considered composed of 14 sports encompassing 18 disciplines and 102 events.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Baseball, Glima (as the second Olympic demonstration of the sport after 1908 Summer Olympics) and Gotland sports were unofficial demonstration sports.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] This was also the first year art competitions were held at the Olympics.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The athletic events saw the introduction of a fully automatic timing system developed by R.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] It involved attaching electromagnets to chronometers in a system which attached a control lamp to the starting gun for each race.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] This resulted in the firing of the gun starting a timer which was then stopped by one of the judges at the finishing line.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The final of the men's 100 metres was expected to be a mostly American affair, and it ended up with six athletes, only one of whom was not from the United States.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] It suffered from seven false starts before the athletes finally got away, with Ralph Craig winning the gold medal by 60 centimetres (24 in) in front of second place Alvah Meyer.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Donald Lippincott won bronze, 15 cm behind the second man.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Shizo Kanakuri, a Japanese marathon runner, went missing during the race.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] He lost consciousness by heatstroke and a farming family helped him to stop at a party taking place in a villa on the marathon route in order to quench his thirst, then caught a train to Stockholm and left the country the next day.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] He returned to Japan without notifying race officials.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Fifty years later, after being invited back by the Swedish authorities, he completed the race with an (unofficial) time of 54 years, 8 months, 6 days, 8 hours, 32 minutes and 20.3 seconds.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Portuguese Francisco Lázaro died from heat exhaustion while running the marathon, the only athlete to die during the running of an Olympic marathon.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] In addition to the physical toll of the event, the reported split time for the 5 km checkpoint at Stocksund (2:17:20 after a 1:48:00 start) implies an unusually slow 29:20 opening segment, followed by an unrealistically fast 10 km pace.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Martin has noted this discrepancy as a likely timing error.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] American Jim Thorpe won the pentathlon and the newly created decathlon.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Thorpe's gold medals were stripped by the International Olympic Committee in 1913, after the IOC learned that Thorpe had taken expense money for playing baseball, violating contemporary Olympic amateurism rules, before the 1912 Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] This moved everyone else up in the rankings.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] In 1982, the IOC was convinced that the disqualification had been improper, as no protest against Thorpe's eligibility had been brought within the required 30 days, and reinstated Thorpe's medals.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The replicas were presented to his children in 1983, 30 years after Thorpe's death.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Finally, in 2022, the IOC posthumously declared Thorpe as the sole winner of the pentathlon and decathlon events after extensive consultations with his former competitors' families who said they had always viewed Thorpe as the winner.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] New Olympic records were set in the majority of track and field events, with only the men's 200 metres, 10 km walk, standing high jump, standing broad jump, hop, step and jump, and the hurdle competitions failing to have new records set.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Tell Berna captured a gold for the 3000m and Henry S.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] "Harry" Babcock took gold for the pole vault, setting an Olympic Record at 3.95m.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Hannes Kolehmainen was the most successful in setting records at the games, with new Olympic Records set in the 5,000, 10,000 metre and cross country races.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The cycling events at the 1912 Games were limited to a road race around Lake Mälaren, which had already been a successful route for a yearly cycling race.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Although not originally in the schedule, several countries requested that track cycling be added; however, the organizing committee stuck by their plans not to build a new track cycling stadium as the only one in Stockholm had been destroyed in order for the Olympic Stadium to be built.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] In addition, Germany had specifically requested Cycle-Polo and Figure-Cycling to be added to the programme, both of which requests were turned down by the committee.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] It was decided to hold the road race as a time trial, and to outlaw any non-competitive cyclists acting as pacemakers.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Nineteen nations entered 151 athletes into the competition, which was a greater number than expected by the committee.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The largest group was from Great Britain, who had entered twelve competitors from England, another twelve from Scotland, and a further nine from Ireland.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The race began on 7 July, with the athletes leaving in groups.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The first group left at 2am, with the remaining groups leaving at intervals of two minutes.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The distance raced was 318 kilometres (198 mi), with South African Rudolph Lewis winning the gold medal in the individual race.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Frederick Grubb of Great Britain won the silver medal, and Carl Schutte of the United States won the bronze.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] However, the average positions of the Swedish team were better than their competitors', and so the Swedish team won the gold medal for the team competition.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The silver and bronze medals followed the individual victories, going to Great Britain and the United States respectively – giving Grubb and Schutte a second medal each of the same varieties.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] All of the medals in the men's competitions were split between the diving teams of the Sweden and Germany.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The men's high dive was a Swedish white out, with Swedish divers taking all three medal positions.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Erik Adlerz took the gold medal, and proceeded to take the gold medal for Sweden in the 10 metre platform too.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Albert Zürner took the silver for Germany, and Gustaf Blomgren won the bronze medal for Sweden.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Another white out occurred in the 3 metre springboard with all three medals going to the German team, with Paul Günther taking gold, Hans Luber in the silver medal position and Kurt Behrens in bronze.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] A 10-metre platform event also took place for women, with Sweden taking two more medals, Greta Johansson in gold and Lisa Regnell in silver.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Great Britain's Isabelle White won the bronze medal.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The remaining finalists were all from Sweden.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Equestrian made its first appearance at a modern Olympics in the 1912 Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Although competitions involving horse riding had been included in the programme of 1900, this was the first appearance of modern Olympic staples such as dressage, eventing and show jumping.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] It was expected that the competitors would be military personnel as they would have had the cavalry experience to compete.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The competition was split between the military competitions, prize riding and prize jumping.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] In the military competition, seven countries put forward competitors for the individual and team eventing.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Each nation put forward four athletes with the exception of Denmark, which only put forward three.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Some of the countries also nominated reserves in addition to their main athletes.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The total length of the course was 55 kilometres (34 mi) with the start and finish both in the grounds of the Field Riding Club.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The heat was such on the day of the event that competitors lost as much as 4.5 pounds (2.0 kg) in weight.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Swede Axel Nordlander won the individual competition, and led the Swedish eventing team to victory as well, earning himself two gold medals.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] In second place in the individual competition was German Friedrich von Rochow, who also earned a second silver medal as the team from Germany placed second overall.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Only the bronze medals were split up between nationalities, with the American team including Guy Vernor Henry, Jr. taking the bronze for the team event, while Frenchman Jacques Cariou won the individual medal.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Two additional countries entered for the dressage, although only Sweden entered the maximum number of competitors.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The event resulted in Sweden taking all three medals, with the gold going to Carl Bonde, the silver to Gustaf Adolf Boltenstern and the bronze to Hans von Blixen-Finecke.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The team event saw Sweden take another gold medal, with the French team second and the German team, featuring Prince Friedrich Karl of Prussia, in the bronze medal position.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The foil competition became a full Olympic event, having appeared at the 1908 Games as a demonstration sport.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Nedo Nadi and Pietro Speciale of Italy took the gold and silver medals respectively, and Richard Verderber of Austria placed third.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] There were individual and team events in both épée and sabre.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The épée team event saw Belgium take the gold medal and Great Britain and the Netherlands in second and third place respectively.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] A member of the Belgian team went on to take the individual title as well, with Paul Anspach taking the gold medal.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Ivan Joseph Martin Osiier of Denmark took the silver medal, and another Belgian who was not in the team event, Philippe le Hardy de Beaulieu, won the bronze medal.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The sabre competition was dominated by the competitors from Hungary, with their team taking the gold medal over Austria and the Netherlands.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The individual competition saw a shut out by Hungarian athletes with Jenő Fuchs winning the overall competition, Béla Békessy in second and Ervin Mészáros in third.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Thirteen countries signalled their intention to enter football teams for the 1912 Olympics.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] A standard cup tie system was implemented, with the final deciding the gold and silver medallists and a third/fourth position playoff deciding the bronze medal winner.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Only FIFA affiliated teams were allowed to take part, with the public draw for the tournament taking place on 18 June 1911.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The tournament itself started on 29 June.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] In the first round Finland defeated Italy 3–2, Austria beat Germany 5–1 and the Netherlands emerged victorious over Sweden 4–3.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The team from Great Britain, who had won the gold medal at the 1908 Summer Games, were given a bye to the second round, where they faced Hungary and won 7–0.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Finland also won their match, defeating Russia 2–1.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Denmark matched the British scoreline, winning 7–0 against Norway, and the Netherlands won against Austria 3–1.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The semi final matches pitted Great Britain against Finland, where they won 4–0, and Denmark against the Netherlands, ending in a 4–1 victory for Denmark.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The Netherlands won the third/fourth place playoff by the biggest scoreline of the tournament, beating Finland 9–0.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Later on the same day the final was played in the Olympic Stadium, where Great Britain retained its gold medal against Denmark in front of 25,000 spectators.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Goals from Harold Walden, Arthur Berry and two from Gordon Hoare helped Britain to win by a margin of 4–2.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The gymnastic competition at the 1912 Games featured a single individual competition and three team events in addition to a variety of displays by the various teams.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The Swedish team naturally won the Gymnastics event of the Swedish system, referred to in the programme as "Team Competition I", with fellow Scandinavian teams Denmark and Norway taking the second and third positions.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The all around team competition came second, with Italy taking the gold.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] In addition, one of the Italian team members, Alberto Braglia, won the individual gold for the same event.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Louis Ségura of the French team won the individual silver, while another member of the Italian team, Adolfo Tunesi, won the individual bronze.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The all around team competition saw Hungary take the silver medal and the team from Great Britain in third place.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The final team competition allowed for a free choice of movements and apparatus.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] This was another all Scandinavian affair, with the Norwegian team emerging victorious, Finland in second and Denmark in the bronze medal position.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Modern pentathlon was competed for at the 1912 Games, marking its first appearance in the Olympics.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] It was for these games that the five events of shooting, swimming, equestrian, fencing and cross country running were decided to make up the pentathlon.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The competition was spread out across five days from 7 through to 12 July, ending with the cross country race.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Only men participated in the event, although a woman named Helen Preece was briefly enrolled to compete until the organizing committee ultimately denied her entry.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] For the shooting element, each competitor was allowed to bring their own pistol.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The shooting part of the competition was won by Gösta Åsbrink, with Georg de Laval and Gösta Lilliehöök in second and third place respectively, all three representing Sweden.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The swimming event was three lengths, each of 100 metres (330 ft), with the athletes split into eight heats and times going forward to calculate positions.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Ralph Clilverd of Great Britain won this event, with Edmond Bernhardt of Austria in second and de Laval in third.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The fencing competition saw each competitor face off against each other.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Several opponents were noted for their particular skill in the event with Åke Grönhagen of Sweden coming first with 24 wins, Jean de Mas Latrie of France second with 23, Sidney Stranne of Sweden in third with 21 and Patton of the United States close behind with 20.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Thirteen of the competitors cleared the equestrian course without any penalties, with Grönhagen winning the event, Bror Mannström of Sweden in second and de Laval third.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The cross country run was over 4,000 metres and started in the Olympic Stadium itself.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The event was run as a time trial with competitors leaving one minute apart.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] As this was the final event, the winning competitors were announced after the race, with Lilliehöök winning the gold medal, Åsbrink taking silver and de Laval, bronze.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The highest placed non-Swedish competitor was Patton, who finished fifth.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The rowing events at the 1912 Olympics did not prove popular with the public.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] This was put down to the "fatigue" of the public due to the volume of sporting events.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The eight competition was split into heats, with two teams in each heat.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The two British crews were lucky not to be drawn against each other, with the team from Leander Club facing New College, Oxford in the final.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Leander won by a length with a time of 6:15.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The coxed four followed a similar format to the eights, with the German team from Ludwigshafener Ruderverein defeating Britain's Thames Rowing Club in the final.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The competition for the coxed four, inriggers was much smaller, with only four nations competing.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The Danish team defeated Sweden in the final.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The single sculls heats proved controversial with the first round race between Mart Kuusik and Alfred Heinrich being re-run after a protest by Heinrich.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] In addition, Cecil McVilly was disqualified in the first round after colliding with the boat of Martin Stahnke.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Wally Kinnear of Great Britain defeated Polydore Veirman of Belgium in the final, with Kinnear winning the matchup easily.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The yachts for the sailing competition assembled at Nynäshamn on 19 July, along with the other vessels that were to take part in an Olympic regatta.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The racing itself started the following day with the 12 metre class.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] There were only three nations and yachts competing in this event, the hosts Sweden, as well as Norway and Finland.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Norway won the gold medal, Sweden the silver and Finland came in last place, winning bronze.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The 10 metre class had the same number of countries entering it, although this time Sweden entered two yachts and Russia competed instead of Norway.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The Swedish yacht *Kitty* was the winning vessel, with the Finnish boat in second and the Russians coming third.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] A slightly improved field was featured in the 8 metre class, with four countries entering two yachts each.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The medals were awarded to exactly the same nations as the 12 metre class, another all Scandinavian affair.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The 6 metre class saw the most diverse field of any of the sailing events at the 1912 Olympics: six countries entered a total of nine yachts.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] France and Denmark competed in their only sailing event, along with Sweden, sending two yachts each.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Those three nations were the successful in the event, with the French yacht *Mac Miche* taking the gold, the Danish *Nurdug II* taking silver and the Swedish *Kerstin* placing third.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] There were eighteen shooting events at the 1912 Olympics, of which eight were team events.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The competition was split predominantly into three sections: military rifle shooting, shooting with miniature rifles, pistols and revolvers, and clay bird and running deer shooting.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The Swedish and American competitors were the most successful at the competition, with seven gold medals each, although Sweden won a total of seventeen medals while the United States team won fourteen.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] 64-year-old Oscar Swahn, part of the Swedish single shot running deer team, is still the oldest gold medal winner in Olympic history.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] In swimming, Hawaiian Duke Kahanamoku won the 100 metre freestyle for the United States, who also saw Harry Hebner win gold in the 100 metre backstroke.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The Canadian team also took two gold medals, both by George Hodgson in the 400 and 1,500 metre events.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The German swimming team won all three medals in the 200 metre breaststroke, with the gold going to Walter Bathe, who won a further gold in the 400 metre breaststroke.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The Australasian team was victorious in the men's relay, with the United States finishing in the silver medal position and Great Britain placing third.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The 1912 Games saw the implementation of swimming events for women, with the 100 metre freestyle and 400 metre team relay taking place.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Fanny Durack won the individual contest, breaking the world record for the distance in the fourth heat.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Her fellow Australian Mina Wylie won the silver medal, and Jennie Fletcher of Great Britain came third to take the bronze medal.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The British team had further success in the women's relay, winning the team relay with the German team in second place and the Austrian team in third.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Because only four countries entered the relay there were no heats; only a final was held.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The United States did not field a women's team.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] New Olympic Records were set in all swimming events at the 1912 Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Tennis on covered courts was agreed initially for the 1912 Games, with competitions run for gentlemen's singles and doubles, ladies' singles, and mixed doubles.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The outdoor tournament was confirmed once the Östermalm Athletic Grounds were completed in late 1911, with the plans modified to have both indoor and outdoor tournaments.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Six countries sent players for the covered court competitions, with representatives from Sweden, Great Britain, Denmark, France, Australasia, and Bohemia appearing.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Included in this lineup was Australasia's only competitor, Anthony Wilding from New Zealand, who was also the reigning Wimbledon gentlemen's champion.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The indoor knockout competition started on 5 May, and continued as expected until the semi-final round where Wilding was beaten by Britain's Charles P.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The British player met Frenchman André Gobert in the final, but Gobert was victorious over the Englishman in straight sets.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Wilding took the bronze medal in a playoff against another British player, Arthur Lowe.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The outdoors tennis competition saw 70 players enter from 12 nations.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] However, Great Britain did not enter any competitors as the dates of the outdoor competition clashed with the 1912 Wimbledon Championships, despite attempts by the British authorities to convince the Olympic organizing committee to change the dates.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Other noted tennis players refused to compete at the Olympics and instead attended Wimbledon.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The gold and silver medals in the gentlemen's singles ended up being decided between two South Africans, with Charles Winslow and Harold Kitson playing each other.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The duo also competed as a pair in the gentlemen's doubles and took the gold medal, beating the Austrians Felix Pipes and Arthur Zborzil.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Marguerite Broquedis of France defeated Dorothea Koring of Germany in the ladies' singles for the gold medal.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] In the mixed doubles Koring teamed up with Heinrich Schomburgk to win the gold, the duo defeating Sigrid Fick and Gunnar Setterwall of Sweden in the final.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The tug of war competition was scheduled to take place between 7 and 12 July, with two matches taking place each day.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] However, out of the five countries which elected to enter the competition, only two actually appeared.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Great Britain arrived for its match against Bohemia, but the opposition team was nowhere to be found.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The same thing happened once more for the second match, with the Swedish team, made up of policemen from Stockholm, arriving to find that the Austrian team had not arrived.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Sweden was announced as the winners of the match in the Austrians' absence.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] On the second day of the competition, Great Britain took on Sweden, the only occasion where both teams actually turned up for the bout.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The British team were made up of the winners of the gold medal in the same event at the 1908 Games, with the exception of John Sewell and Mathias Hynes.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] As the British team also consisted of policemen, the bout ended up effectively being between the City of London Police and the Stockholm Police, with the Swedish team winning 2–0.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Due to the non-appearance of the team from Luxembourg, that one match ended up being the entire tug of war event at the 1912 Olympics.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Sweden was awarded the gold medal and Great Britain the silver.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The water polo tournament was set up on a modified elimination system as there were six teams entered.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The first round saw the British team defeating the Belgian team, Sweden defeating the French team and Austria defeating Hungary.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Lots were drawn to determine which match would take place in the second round as there were three teams left in the competition.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Great Britain were drawn to face Sweden, who they defeated.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Austria automatically qualified for the final against the winner of the Britain-Sweden matchup.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Great Britain won the gold medal in the event, defeating Austria 8–0.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Playoff matches were then played between each pair of defeated teams in order to decide the second and third places.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Sweden and Belgium played off after a further three matches to decide the silver and bronze medal positions, with Sweden emerging victorious 4–2.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The nations at the 1912 Games entered a total of 267 wrestlers, although the actual competitors who appeared in Sweden were fewer, with 171 actually turning up to compete.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Greco-Roman wrestling was the only style of wrestling competed for at the Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The bouts took place in the open air in an area of the Olympic stadium, with the wrestlers split according to weight into five divisions: featherweight, lightweight, middleweight A (later referred to as middleweight), middleweight B (later referred to as light heavyweight) and heavyweight.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The skills of the competitors from Finland were noted in the featherweight competition, with Kaarlo Koskelo taking the gold medal, while German Georg Gerstäcker took silver and a further medal went to Finland with Otto Lasanen taking bronze.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The lightweight class drew the most attention from the public, with Emil Väre winning gold after beating all of his opponents by pin rather than by points.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Swedish wrestlers Gustaf Malmström and Edvin Mattiasson took the silver and bronze medals respectively.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Claes Johanson won Sweden's only gold medal in the middleweight competition, with his fellow finalist from Russia, Martin Klein, retiring before fighting Johanson in the final.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] This was due to the semi-final match between Klein and Alfred Asikainen of Finland lasting 11 hours and forty minutes, although they took breaks for refreshments every half-hour.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Klein was awarded the silver medal and Asikainen the bronze.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The light heavyweight competition saw another marathon length match, with the bout between Anders Ahlgren of Sweden and Ivar Böhling of Finland for the gold medal lasting more than nine hours.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The match was then declared a draw with both athletes being awarded the silver medal as neither won the match.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The bronze medal went to Hungary's Béla Varga, who was defeated by Ahlgren in the semi-final match.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Yrjö Saarela of Finland was victorious in the heavyweight competition after having placed second in the light heavyweight event at the 1908 Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Johan Olin took another medal for Finland with the silver and Søren Marinus Jensen repeated his bronze medal at the 1908 Olympics with another for Denmark.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The 1912 Summer Olympics saw the introduction of art competitions at the Summer Olympics.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Events were implemented for literature, sculpture, painting, architecture and music.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Walter Winans won the gold medal for his sculpture, *An American Trotter*, which added to his previous gold medal for the running deer (double shot) competition at the 1908 Olympics and the silver medal in the running deer competition in 1912.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Baron Pierre de Coubertin, President of the IOC and founder of the modern Olympic movement, won the gold medal for literature.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] He actually entered the competition under the pseudonyms of Georges Hohrod and Martin Eschbach from Germany.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] With the exception of the sculpture competition, only gold medals were issued.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Italian Riccardo Barthelemy won the medal for music with his *Olympic Triumphal March*, and fellow countryman Giovanni Pellegrini won the gold for painting.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The Swiss architects Eugène-Edouard Monod and Alphonse Laverrière shared the gold for their stadium design.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The sole silver medal, for sculpture, went to Frenchman Georges Dubois for his *Model of the entrance to a modern stadium*.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] In the evening of 7 July, demonstrations took place in the Olympic Stadium of sports from the Swedish island of Gotland.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] These began at 7:30pm with a demonstration of Pärk, a type of tennis with seven players a side.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] At the same time, at the other end of the stadium, a type of Icelandic wrestling called Glima was demonstrated.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Once those displays had concluded, further demonstrations were made of the Swedish sport varpa, similar to quoits, and stångstörtning, a version of the caber toss.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The three disciplines showcased were pärk, varpa and stångstörtning.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Baseball was also demonstrated at the Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] A game was played between the United States, the nation where the game was developed, and Sweden, the host nation.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The game was held on Monday, 15 July 1912 and started at 10 a.m. on the Ostermalm Athletic Grounds in Stockholm.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The Americans were represented by various members of the American Olympic track and field athletics delegation, while the Swedish team was the Vesterås Baseball Club, which had been formed in 1910 as the first baseball club in Sweden.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Four of the Americans played for Sweden, as the Swedish pitchers and catchers were inexperienced.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] One Swede eventually relieved Adams and Nelson, the American pitchers.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Six innings were played, with the Americans not batting in the sixth and allowing the Swedes to have six outs in their half of the inning.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The game was umpired by George Wright, a retired American National League baseball player.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Twenty-eight nations competed at the 1912 Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Egypt participated for the first time, as did Luxembourg, Iceland, Portugal, and Serbia.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Japan also made their Olympic debut, marking the first appearance of an Asian country at an Olympic Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Chile made its first appearance as a national team, with fourteen athletes attending the Games, although it had previously entered one individual at the 1896 Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] This was also the first time that athletes from Armenia had competed in the Olympics, as part of the team from Turkey (the officially recognised name for the Ottoman Empire).
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Serbia's appearance was the only time it attended an Olympic Games as an independent nation until the 2008 Summer Olympics, almost one hundred years later.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The only nation that participated in the previous games in London 1908 but was absent in Stockholm 1912 was Argentina.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Austria and Hungary competed as two sovereign countries.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The polity known as Austria-Hungary is mistakenly considered a single sovereign country, while in reality they were two sovereign states in real union with a single monarch who was titled both emperor of Austria and king of Hungary.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] At the time, Australasia (Australia and New Zealand), Canada and South Africa were all part of the British Empire.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Egypt was de jure under the control of Turkey, but had been de facto run by the British since 1882.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] This was the last Olympics that allowed "private entries", i.e. individual athletes that were not part of a country's officially selected team.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] Arnold Jackson was one such private entry; he won the 1500 metres by 0.1 seconds, ahead of an American trio, in what was acclaimed at the time to be "the greatest race ever run".
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] His medal is still credited to the United Kingdom, however.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] These are the top 10 nations that won medals at the 1912 Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1912-summer-olympics] The medals themselves included solid gold medals, the last time these were given out.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] Olympiade***) and commonly known as **Antwerp 1920** (French: ***Anvers 1920***; Dutch and German: ***Antwerpen 1920***), were an international multi-sport event held in 1920 in Antwerp, Belgium.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] In March 1912, during the 13th session of the IOC, Belgium's bid to host the 1920 Summer Olympics was made by Baron Édouard de Laveleye, president of the Belgian Olympic Committee and of the Royal Belgian Football Association.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] No fixed host city was proposed at the time.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] The 1916 Summer Olympics, to have been held in Berlin, capital of the German Empire, were cancelled due to World War I.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] When the Olympic Games resumed after the war, Antwerp was awarded the hosting rights to the 1920 Summer Games as a tribute to the Belgian people.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] The aftermath of the war and the Paris Peace Conference affected the Olympic Games not only due to new states being created but also by sanctions against the nations that lost the war and were blamed for starting it.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] Hungary, Germany, Austria, Bulgaria, and the Ottoman Empire were banned from competing in the Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] Soviet Russia had just emerged from the Civil War and chose not to attend the Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] Germany did not return to Olympic competition until 1928 and instead hosted a series of games called Deutsche Kampfspiele, starting with the Winter edition of 1922 (which predated the first Winter Olympics).
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold and overall medals at the 1920 Summer Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] In March 1912, during the 13th session of the IOC, the bid on behalf of Belgium to host the 1920 Summer Olympics was made by Baron Édouard de Laveleye, president of the Belgian Olympic Committee and of the Royal Belgian Football Association.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] The organizing committee was created on 9 August 1913.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] Among the 22 vice presidents of the committee were people with a military or industrial background and further people from sports organizations, like Paul Havenith, president of the football and athletics club K.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] Beerschot V.A.C., and Nicolaas Jan Cupérus, president of the Belgian Gymnastics Federation.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] The first action of the committee was to send an official letter to the IOC in Paris, confirming Antwerp as the city for the Belgian Olympic bid.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] With Antwerp confirmed as the Olympic Games host, Belgium began reconstructing the Beerschot Stadium into the Olympisch Stadion.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] Construction on the new Olympic stadium began in July 1919 and finished in May 1920.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] In 1914, a 109-page brochure was created to promote the idea of Antwerp as a host city for the Olympics: *Aurons-nous la VIIème Olympiade à Anvers?* (*Will we have the 7th Olympiad at Antwerp?*).
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] It was sent to all IOC members and was used during the 6th Olympic Congress in Paris in 1914, where the candidacies of Amsterdam (which would eventually host the 1928 Summer Olympics), Antwerp, Budapest, and Rome (which would eventually host the 1960 Summer Olympics) were discussed.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] Despite a slight preference at the time for Budapest, no final choice was made, and the outbreak of World War I soon afterwards prevented any further progress.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] In 1915, Lyon made a bid for the 1920 Games, but after some discussion, they agreed to support Antwerp and postpone their bid until 1924 if Antwerp was liberated in time to organize the Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] The support for Belgium by cousin country France, then the leading country of the IOC, also meant that Amsterdam and Budapest (in an enemy state) had no chance for the 1920 games against Antwerp.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] New candidacies from American cities did not have that disadvantage, and bids were received from Cleveland, Philadelphia, and Atlanta (which would eventually host the 1996 Summer Olympics), while Cuba also submitted a bid for Havana.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] However, shortly after the armistice in November 1918, the IOC decided to award Antwerp their first preference if they were still willing to host the 1920 Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] In March 1919, the Belgian Olympic Committee decided to go ahead with the organization of the Games: on 5 April 1919, at a meeting in Lausanne, Antwerp was officially declared the host city for the games of the VIIth Olympiad.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] The 1920 Summer Games organizers had very little time to prepare.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] The time between the IOC's decision of choosing Antwerp as the host city and the opening ceremony was 1 year, 4 months, and 9 days, making this the shortest time for a host city to plan and organize an Olympic edition.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] An executive committee was established on 17 April 1919, with Henri de Baillet-Latour as chairman and Alfred Verdyck, the secretary of the Belgian Union of Football Clubs, as general secretary.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] Seven commissions were created to deal with finances, accommodation, press relations, propaganda, schedules, transport, and festivities.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] Finances and scheduling proved to be the two hardest parts to tackle: the program of events was not published until February 1920, six months before the official start of the Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] Between 23 and 30 April 1920, an ice hockey tournament marked the early start of the Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] Held in the "Palais de Glace" or Ice Palace in Antwerp, it was the first time that ice hockey was an Olympic sport.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] The first stone of the new Olympisch Stadion was laid on 4 July 1919 by Jan De Vos, mayor of Antwerp, and inaugurated less than a year later on 23 May 1920 with a gymnastics demonstration.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] When the Olympic Games began, the stadium was still unfinished, with some events being built over fortifications and others using existing locations.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] The athletes' quarters were crowded, and athletes slept on folding cots.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] The nautical stadium, or Stade Nautique d'Antwerp, was built at the end of the Jan Van Rijswijcklaan, using the city ramparts there as a spectator's stand.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] Other events, like shooting, boxing, and equestrian sports, were held at pre-existing locations in and around Antwerp and as far away as Ostend.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] The number of spectators was low throughout Antwerp's Summer Olympics because few people could afford tickets.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] In the closing days of the Olympic Games, students were allowed to attend the event for free.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] After the conclusion of the Olympic Games, Belgium recorded a loss of more than 600 million francs.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] There were 162 events in 28 disciplines that were part of the Olympic program in 1920.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] Women's water polo was a demonstration sport.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] The 1920 Summer Olympics featured seventeen sports venues.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] This marked the first time that the football tournament was spread throughout the country, which has mostly been the case since.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] A total of 29 nations participated in the Antwerp Games, only one more than in 1912, as Germany, Austria, Hungary, Bulgaria, and Turkey were not invited, having lost World War I and sanctioned for starting it.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] From the newly created European states, only Estonia took part, as Czechoslovakia succeeded Bohemia and the Kingdom of Serbs, Croats, and Slovenes succeeded Serbia, with both nations having sent athletes prior to World War I (in the case of Bohemia, as part of the Austrian Empire).
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] Soviet Russia was busy with the Polish-Soviet War and therefore was unable to form an Olympic team (Poland, in turn, had never participated in the games before, only doing so in later editions).
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] Brazil and Monaco competed as nations at the Olympic Games for the first time.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] New Zealand, which had competed as part of a combined team with Australia in 1908 and 1912, competed on its own for the first time.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] The games marked the return of Argentina and India to the competitions.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] At the time, Australia, New Zealand, Canada, India, and South Africa were all part of the British Empire.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] Egypt was a British protectorate (a state not part of the British Empire but nonetheless administered by the United Kingdom).
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] As the local Olympic Organizing Committee went bankrupt during the Antwerp 1920 Games, no official report of the Games was ever produced.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] The documents of the Games were archived at the Belgium Olympic Committee headquarters in Brussels.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1920 Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1920-summer-olympics] These were the first Olympics where the host nation failed to win the most medals overall.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] The **1924 Summer Olympics** (French: *Jeux olympiques d'été de 1924*), officially the **Games of the VIII Olympiad** (French: *Jeux de la VIIIe olympiade*) and officially branded as **Paris 1924**, were an international multi-sport event held in Paris, France.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony was held on 5 July, but some competitions had already started on 4 May.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] The Games were the second to be hosted by Paris (after 1900), making it the first city to host the Olympics twice.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] The selection process for the 1924 Summer Olympics consisted of six bids, and Paris was selected ahead of Amsterdam, Barcelona, Los Angeles, Prague, and Rome.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] The selection was made at the 20th IOC Session in Lausanne in 1921.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] The cost of these Games was estimated to be 10,000,000 F (equivalent to €10.9 million in 2025).
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] With total receipts at 5,496,610 F (equivalent to €5.97 million in 2025), the Olympics resulted in a hefty loss despite daily crowds of up to 60,000.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold and overall medals, having 229 athletes competing compared to France's 401.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] This would be the last Summer Games hosted by France until 2024.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] 126 events in 23 disciplines, comprising 17 sports, were part of the Olympic program in 1924.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] The Jeux de L’Enfance, a program of youth sports competitions and activities, were held by Olympic organizers alongside the Games in cooperation with the YMCA.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] Seventeen sports venues were used in the 1924 Summer Olympics.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] Stade de Colombes served as the final venue for the 1938 FIFA World Cup between Italy and Hungary.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] A total of 44 nations were represented at the 1924 Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] Germany was still absent, having not been invited by the Organizing Committee.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] China (although it did not compete), Ecuador, Ireland, Lithuania, and Uruguay attended the Olympic Games for the first time, while the Philippines competed for first time in an Olympic Games as a nation (though it first participated in the 1900 Summer Olympic Games).
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] Latvia and Poland also attended the Summer Olympic Games for the first time (having both appeared earlier at the 1924 Winter Olympics in Chamonix).
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] The 1924 Olympics saw a return of the following nations: Austria, Bulgaria, Cuba, Haiti, Hungary, Mexico, Romania and Turkey.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] At the time, Australia, New Zealand, Canada, South Africa and Ireland were all dominions of the British Empire.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] India was also part of British Empire, but was not a dominion.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] United States, France, Brazil, Japan, etc) and the international community as a whole (i.e League of Nations) the term dominion, used internally in the British Empire, was very ambiguous, meaning "something between a colony and state".
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] It was only years later with the Statute of Westminster 1931 that this ambiguity would be dispelled.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] And Philippines was an unincorporated territory and commonwealth of the United States.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] These are the nations that won medals the 1924 Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] The 1924 Summer Olympics also included art competitions across five disciplines: architecture, literature, music, painting, and sculpture, for works inspired by sport-related themes, were medal-eligible events at the time.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] Art competitions were held from the 1912 Summer Olympics until the 1948 Summer Olympics, but were discontinued over the amateurism controversy.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] Medals in art competitions are no longer recognized by the IOC as part of the total medal count.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] In architecture, no gold medal was awarded while the silver was awarded to the pair of Alfréd Hajós and Dezső Lauber of Hungary.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] Hajós became one of only two Olympians ever to have won medals in both sport (two golds in swimming at the 1896 Summer Olympics) and art Olympic competitions.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] The bronze was awarded to Julien Médecin of Monaco, who became the first Monégasque competitor to win an Olympic medal.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] In literature, one gold, which was awarded to Géo-Charles of France, two silvers to Josef Petersen of Denmark and Margaret Stuart of Great Britain, and two bronzes to Charles Gonnet of France and Oliver Gogarty of Ireland, were awarded.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] Two compositions, entitled "The Land Where the Rose is Grown" and "O Vigila (now let the games begin)", that were part of the literature competition, were also part of the music competitions.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] The compositions were made by George Bamber of Great Britain, though no medals were awarded in the music competition as the jury could not reach a consensus to award medals for any of the competitors.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] In painting, Jean Jacoby of Luxembourg won the gold medal, becoming the first Luxembourgish competitor to win an Olympic gold medal, Jack Butler Yeats of Ireland won the silver, becoming the first Irish competitor to win an Olympic medal, and Johan van Hell of the Netherlands won the bronze.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] In sculpture, Konstantinos Dimitriadis of Greece won the gold medal, Frantz Heldenstein of Luxembourg won the silver, and two bronze medals were awarded, one to Jean René Gauguin of Denmark and the other to Claude-Léon Mascaux of France.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] The 1924 Summer Olympics was the second edition of the Summer Olympics to be held in Paris.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] 100 years later, the city has hosted the games once again with the 2024 Summer Olympics, marking its third time, becoming the second city ever to host the Summer Olympics three times (after London, which hosted the 1908, 1948, and 2012 Games).
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] Paris 2024 also marks the centenary of Chamonix 1924, which in turn marks the centenary of the Winter Olympics; making Paris 2024 the sixth Olympic Games hosted by France (three Summer Olympics and three Winter Olympics), and the first French Olympics since the 1992 Winter Games in Albertville.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] Notable debuts of participating countries for the Paris 1924 Olympics include Ireland, Latvia, Lithuania, Philippines, Poland, Romania, and Uruguay; all of which celebrated their centenary participation at the 2024 Summer Olympics back in Paris.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] One venue from the 1924 Games was used in the 2024 Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] The extensively renovated and downsized main stadium, known since 1928 as Stade Olympique Yves-du-Manoir, hosted field hockey.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] The last surviving competitor of the 1924 Summer Olympics was Croatian swimmer Ivo Pavelić, who died on 22 February 2011 at the age of 103; he competed for Yugoslavia, which Croatia was part of at the time.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1924-summer-olympics] Continuation of Jeux de L’Enfance, games for youth sports and competition, from the Paris 1924 was embodied through the creation of Youth Olympics Games inaugurating in Singapore with the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics with 3,600 athletes aged 14–18 from 204 nations competing in 201 events in 26 sports.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] After Japan declared in 1938 that it would be unable to host the 1940 Olympics in Tokyo due to the ongoing Second Sino-Japanese War, Helsinki had been selected to host the 1940 Summer Olympics, which were then cancelled due to World War II.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Tokyo eventually hosted the games in 1964.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Helsinki is the northernmost city at which a summer Olympic Games have been held.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] With London hosting the 1948 Olympics, 1952 is the most recent time when two consecutive summer Olympic Games were held entirely in Europe.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The 1952 Summer Olympics was the last of the two consecutive Olympics to be held in Northern Europe, following the 1952 Winter Olympics in Oslo, Norway.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] They were also the Olympic Games at which the most world records were broken until they were surpassed by the 2008 Summer Games in Beijing.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Bahamas, Guatemala, Hong Kong, Indonesia, Israel, Netherlands Antilles, Nigeria, the People's Republic of China, Saarland, the Soviet Union, Thailand, and Vietnam made their Olympic debuts at the 1952 Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The United States won the most gold and overall medals at these Olympics.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Inspired by the success of the Swedish 1912 Olympics, Finnish sports fans began to arouse the idea of their own Olympic Games: for example, Erik von Frenckell publicly presented his dreams of the Finnish Olympic Games at the opening of the 1915 Töölön Pallokenttä.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] As the Olympic success continued in the 1920s, enthusiasm for one's own Olympics grew, and after the 1920 Antwerp Olympics, Finnish sports leaders began planning to build a stadium in Helsinki in 1920.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Finland's main sports organizations and the City of Helsinki founded the Stadion Foundation in 1927 to get the stadium to Helsinki.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the same year, Ernst Edvard Krogius, who represented Finland on the International Olympic Committee (IOC), announced Finland's willingness to host the competition.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In 1930, preparations for the 1936 Games, which was accelerated by the launch of a design project for the Olympic Stadium.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] However, Helsinki was not a candidate in the first round in 1931, and Berlin won the competition, but Helsinki immediately registered as a candidate for the 1940 Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] World War II broke out on 1 September 1939, with the German–Soviet invasion of Poland, which also drew Britain and France to war.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Despite the aggression, the Organizing Committee of the Olympic Games continued to be optimistic about the preparations for the Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] However, the Soviet invasion of Finland on 30 November 1939, halted planning for the games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] After the Winter War, the Organizing Committee decided to abandon the Games on 20 March 1940 due to the hostilities across Europe, the suspension of preparations caused by the Winter War, and the deplorable economic situation.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] At the meeting of the Finnish Olympic Committee on 20 April 1940, the Olympic Games in Finland were officially canceled.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the meantime, World War II had already expanded, with Germany occupying Denmark and fighting in Norway.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Instead of the Olympic Games, Finland held a Memorial Competitions for Fallen Athletes who died in the Winter War against Russia, at the opening of which actor Eino Kaipainen recited the poem *Silent Winners* written by Yrjö Jylhä.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The memorial competitions were held on the initiative of the sports journalist Sulo Kolkka.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] At the end of World War II, London was awarded the 1948 Summer Olympics after the city was originally granted the 1944 Games, which were canceled due to the war.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Helsinki continued its attempt to have the Games organized and registered as candidates for the 1952 Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] At the IOC Congress in Stockholm on 21 June 1947, Helsinki was chosen as the host city, leaving behind the bids of Amsterdam, Los Angeles, Minneapolis, Detroit, Chicago and Philadelphia.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Helsinki's strengths included the fairly completed venues built for the 1940 Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] After confirmation that Helsinki would host the Games, the "XV Olympia Helsinki 1952" was established as the organizing committee of the Games on 8 September 1947.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Its members were the Finnish Olympic Committee, the Finnish State, the City of Helsinki and 26 various sports organizations.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The mayor of Helsinki Erik von Frenckell was elected chairman of the committee, who at the time also chaired Finnish Football Association.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Akseli Kaskela, Olavi Suvanto and Armas-Eino Martola were elected Vice-Chairs.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Among them, Kaskela and Suvanto were elected on political grounds as representatives of the bourgeois Finnish Sports Federation (SVUL) and the leftist Finnish Workers' Sports Federation (TUL), Martola, on the other hand, got a former officer to lead the organization of the practical arrangements.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Other members of the Organizing Committee were Yrjö Enne, Väinö A.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Karikoski, Urho Kekkonen, Ernst Krogius, William Lehtinen, Aarne K.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Leskinen, Eino Pekkala, Väinö Salovaara and Erik Åström.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In 1948–1949, Karikoski, Kekkonen, Krogius and Lehtinen resigned from the committee, and Lauri Miettinen, Arno Tuurna and Yrjö Valkama were elected to replace them.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the spring of 1952, Ente was replaced by Arvi E.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Heiskanen and as completely new members by Mauno Pekkala and Aaro Tynell.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Erik von Frenckell was the chairman of the organizing committee and the other members were Armas-Eino Martola (competition director), Yrjö Valkama (sports director), Olavi Suvanto (maintenance director), Akseli Kaskela, Aarne K.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In addition, the head of the central office Kallio Kotkas and the head of information Eero Petäjäniemi were involved in the competition organization.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The international political atmosphere was tense when the Helsinki Olympics were held.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] When the IOC held its meeting in Vienna in 1951, many difficult topics were on the agenda.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Cold War was under way, and the situation between Israel and Arab countries, divided Germany had to be addressed as a team, and the Chinese Civil War, with the Chinese Communist Party winning, forming the People's Republic of China and the Republic of China government exiled to Taiwan.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Four years earlier, Japan was not invited to the London Olympics from the losing states of the Second World War.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Olympic Committee of Israel had not yet been recognized, and a successor to the German Olympic Committee, which had been dissolved during World War II, had not yet been established, but all these countries already participated in the Helsinki Games, as did Saarland.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Cold War affected the participation of both the United States and the Soviet Union in the Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The participation of the United States in the Games was decided only after the country had received an assessment of the political situation in Finland from its embassy in Helsinki.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Soviet Union was accepted as a member of the IOC in May 1951, and in December of the same year the country accepted the invitation to the competition, as the country's athletes were in medal condition.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Although the Soviet leadership had previously considered the Games a bourgeois event, the Helsinki Games held propaganda value.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the Soviet Union, billions of rubles were spent on coaching athletes in just one year.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Soviet Union planned to fly its athletes every day between Leningrad and Helsinki.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Another option was for Soviet athletes to stay in the Soviet Porkkalanniemi garrison.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] However, Finland required that all competitors stay in the Olympic village.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] As a compromise solution for the Eastern Bloc athletes, a second Olympic village was established in Espoo, Otaniemi as Soviet leaders wanted them to avoid contact with Western athletes.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Joseph Stalin allowed Soviet athletes to enter the 1952 Summer Olympics because he was sure that they would win the most medals.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] However, American athletes secured more gold and total medals and Stalin afforded more resources for the advancement of elite athletes in the Soviet Union in the build-up to the 1956 Summer Olympics.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The 1952 Games were also threatened with cancellation due to the deteriorating world situation.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Korean War had begun in 1950, which also caused concern in the organizing committee.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] At Von Frenckell's suggestion, the organizing committee decided to take out Lloyd's of London war insurance.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Most of the venues for the competitions were completed prior to the 1940s in anticipation of successful bid attempts, but some expansion and refurbishment work was needed, including the construction of additional stands at the Olympic and Swimming Stadium.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A residential area, Kisakylä (Olympic Village) was built south of Käpylä's Koskelantie to accommodate competitors.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The area, which was built close to the 1940 Olympics, was already the residence of the people of Helsinki at that time.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Just below the opening, the competition area was completed for the use of visitors Kumpula Outdoor Swimming Pool.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Female athletes got their own race village from the Nursing College in Meilahti.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The athletes of the Soviet-led Eastern Bloc stayed in the Teekkarikylä in Otaniemi.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Finnish team lived on the premises of the Santahamina Army School (later the Cadet School, now the National Defence University).
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The City of Helsinki prepared for the Olympics by building a new airport in Seutula (now Helsinki-Vantaan lentoasema), 11-story Hotelli Palace, and the Olympic Pier in South Harbor.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A large electric scoreboard was procured.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] It attracted international attention because it represented the top of its time in the scoreboard field both in terms of its system and its technology.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] OMEGA debuted the OMEGA Time Recorder in Helsinki.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] This all-new quartz clock not only timed the events but also printed out the results.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] This breakthrough technology allowed official Olympic times to be accurate to 1/100 of a second.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] As a result, the company received the prestigious Croix du Mérite Olympique award for their efforts.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In 1950 cable television was tried for the first time in Finland, in the 1952 Olympics people could watch TV sending from the stadium through coaxial cable to Stockmann department store window.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Helsinki paved tens of kilometers of roads, and a myriad of houses were painted.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The city's first traffic lights were installed at the intersection of Aleksanterinkatu and Mikonkatu in October 1951.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Palace Hotel and Vaakuna Hotel among others, were completed for the needs of the guests.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] However, due to the relatively low number of hotels in the city, tent villages were built for tourists in Lauttasaari and Seurasaari, among others.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] However, the preparations for accommodation turned out to be considerably oversized; at its best, the occupancy rate of the 6,000-seat tent village in Lauttasaari had an occupancy of only 8 per cent.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] With the support of the Olympia 1952 committee, Finland's first mini golf courses were completed to entertain guests.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The International Olympic Committee had declared in 1950 that it did not have an official Olympic anthem, but that the organizers could decide their own anthems.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] An anthem competition was held in Finland.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the spring of 1951, a poetry competition was announced, which was surprisingly won by an unknown teacher candidate, Niilo Partanen.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Second and third came the well-known poets Toivo Lyy and Heikki Asunta.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] These winning poems were allowed to be used in the composition competition.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The selection of the 51 compositions by a jury chaired by Jouko Tolonen was also a surprise.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] When the winner was announced on 17 March 1952, an unknown teacher Jaakko Linjama was revealed behind the nickname, who had used Lyy's lyrics in his Olympic Hymn.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The nicknames of the other contestants were not opened.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] This caused a stir, and Arijoutsi, among others, doubted that the victory of the unknown would go to the honor of well-known composers.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] There were well-known members in the competition.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The voters had identified the composing style of Uuno Klami and Aarre Merikanto, among others.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The only Finnish composer who congratulated Linjamaa was Jean Sibelius, who did not take part in the anthem.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Olympic torch was transported by land from Olympia to Athens from where fire's journey continued in a miner's lamp donated by the Saar Olympic Committee on a SAS plane to Aalborg, Denmark.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The glass cover surrounding the lamp was designed by the artist Sakari Tohka.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Olympic torch itself was designed by the artist Aukusti Tuhka.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] From Denmark, the torchlight continued by running, cycling, riding, rowing and paddling to Copenhagen, from where the fire was transported by ferry to Sweden to Malmö.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The journey of the torch across Sweden was carried to Haparanda by 700 messengers, from where it continued to the Finnish side in Tornio.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] On the Finnish-Swedish border bridge, the torch was received by Ville Pörhölä, who brought it to Tornio sports ground.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Olympic torch from Tornio, Greece, was connected to Pallastunturi on 6 July 1952 where it ignited the "midnight sun fire".
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In reality, the Pallastunturi fire was lit with liquefied petroleum gas, because the night in July was cloudy at that time and it was not possible to use the sun as a lighter.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] From Tornio, the torch traveled through Finland to Helsinki.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] It was transported by more than 1,200 people.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Initially, the aim was to transport fire to Helsinki via the Soviet Union, but the matter was not settled through diplomacy by the deadline.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The journey covered a total of 7,870 kilometres on the journey that began on 25 June and ended on 19 July 1952.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The actual Olympic flame was lit for the Olympic Stadium.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The opening ceremony of the Helsinki Olympics was held on 19 July.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Although the weather was rainy and chilly and the Olympic Stadium had no roof but on top of the main auditorium, the stadium was full with 70,435 spectators.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The inaugural march had a record 5,469 people from 67 countries.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] After the march, the countries organized themselves into the central lawn, and the chairman of the organizing committee, Erik von Frenckell, spoke in Finnish, Swedish, French and English.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Paasikivi gave the opening speech, which was the shortest in Olympic history and contained a mistake: it was not the "Fifteenth Olympic Games", but the XV Olympic Games and the 12th World Olympics, due to the 1916, 1940 and 1944 races had been canceled.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The speech was followed by the raising of the Olympic flag and the *Olympic fanfare* composed by Aarre Merikanto.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Olympic flame was lit by running heroes Paavo Nurmi (to the stadium) and Hannes Kolehmainen (to the stadium tower).
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] When Paavo Nurmi was announced to arrive at the stadium, athletes from the participating countries deviated from the formation to see the legend better.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Only the lines of the Soviet Union and Finland remained in the line.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] After the Olympic flame was lit, the Archbishop Ilmari Salomies was due to say a prayer, but German Barbara Rotbraut-Pleyer, nicknamed "White Angel of the Games", had jumped from the auditorium onto the track and ran straight to the speaker's seat.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Organizers quickly removed Pleyer, who had time to say just a few words into the microphone.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Pleyer's purpose was to proclaim a message of peace.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Heikki Savolainen, a gymnast who was competing in his fifth consecutive Olympic games, swore the Olympic oath on behalf of the athletes.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] There were 4,925 athletes from 69 countries, with the Soviet Union making its Olympic debut and Germany participating for the first time since World War II.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A total of 149 events were held in 17 different sports.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The most-medalling athletes of the Games were Viktor Chukarin of the Soviet Union, who won four gymnastics Olympic gold medals, and Czechoslovakia's Emil Zátopek, who won three track golds.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The United States won the most gold and total medals, with 40 and 76.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The host country, Finland, had 6 gold, 3 silver and 13 bronze medals.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Shooting was competed in seven events, six of which (rifle sports) were conducted at the Malmi Shooting Range in moderately difficult wind conditions.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Tough results were still fired in Helsinki, as the top four deer shooting broke world records.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] World records for knee position were also broken in free and small rifles.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Shotgun shooting took place at the Huopalahti shooting range.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Ten countries took medals from the shooting.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Norway was the only country to win two gold medals, with the Soviet Union winning the most medals.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Boris Andreyev was the only Soviet shooter to win two multiple medals.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A Finnish winner was already celebrated in a miniature rifle when Vilho Ylönen had time to play on the radio *Björneborgarnas marsch*.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] However, in an hour-long countdown, the Norwegian Erling Asbjørn Kongshaug was declared the winner of the competition.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The football tournament started even before the official opening, as the one-piece qualifiers took place on 15–16 July in Kotka, Lahti, Tampere, Turku and Helsinki.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] There were 27 countries registered for the tournament, but Saarland and Mexico dropped out before the Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Hungary *Golden Team* won the gold when it knocked down the Yugoslavia in the final with a score of 2–0.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the final, the Olympic Stadium had 58 553 paid spectators, the largest number of spectators in Finland watching a football match.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The first meeting between the Soviet Union and Yugoslavia in football is still amongst the most famous matches.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] On the political level, the Soviet leader Joseph Stalin and the Yugoslav leader Josip Tito split in 1948, which resulted in Yugoslavia being excluded from the Communist Information Bureau.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The origin of the conflict was Tito's refusal to submit to Stalin's interpretations and visions of politics and in process becoming a Soviet satellite state.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Before the match, both Tito and Stalin sent telegrams to their national teams, which showed just how important it was for the two head of states.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Yugoslavia led 5–1, but a Soviet comeback in the last 15 minutes resulted in a 5–5 draw.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The match was replayed, Yugoslavia winning 3–1.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The defeat to the archrivals hit Soviet football hard, and after just three games played in the season, CSKA Moscow, who had made up most of the USSR squad, was forced to withdraw from the league by Joseph Stalin and later disbanded.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Furthermore, Boris Arkadiev, who coached both USSR and CDKA, was stripped of his Merited Master of Sports of the USSR title.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] 23 teams entered basketball, ten of which made it directly to the actual tournament.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The remaining 13 countries took the final six places in the Olympic tournament before the official opening of the Olympic Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In basketball, the gold medal was won by the United States, who defeated Soviet Union in the final 36–25.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The final match was relatively slow-paced, as the Soviet Union tried to keep up with the United States by freezing the game.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The United States had already clearly beat the Soviet Union 86–58 earlier in the tournament.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The bronze was won by Uruguay, who also organized a mass battle after being dissatisfied with the referee's work.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Field hockey was included in the Helsinki Olympic Games in the range of sports on the condition that a maximum of 12 teams register for the Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the end, 16 teams applied for the competition, from which the International Field Hockey Federation selected 12 countries to participate in the competition venue.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Eventually, four countries dropped out of the Games, so the remaining 12 teams that had applied for the competition were able to take part in the Olympic tournament.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The tournament started with two rounds before the Games opened, and the final match was held on 24 July.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] India and Netherlands met in the Velodrome final, with India winning its fifth consecutive gold under captaincy of Kunwar Digvijay Singh with a score of 6–1.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Canoeing competitions were held Taivallahti 27–28 July.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] There were a total of 159 participants in eight men's and women's only races, coming from 21 countries.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Canoeing was a celebration in Finland, as four of the nine sports went to the host country.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In addition, the Finns took one silver and a bronze.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The double gold medalists were Kurt Wires and Yrjö Hietanen who won the kayak duo's 1,000 and 10,000 meters.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the only women's sport, the 500-meter kayak unit, gold was taken by Sylvi Saimo, who was the first Finnish female gold medalist in the summer competitions.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The second most successful country in kayaking was Sweden, which won one gold and three silver.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Helsinki Olympics fencing competitions were held on the Espoo side of the Westend Tennis Hall.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The men competed with Épée, sabre and foil in both personal competition and team competition.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The women had only a personal competition for foil in the program.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] There were 250 men and 37 women from 32 countries.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Italy, Hungary and France were, as usual, the best fencing countries and took all the gold medals.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A total of six countries reached medals.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Mangiarot brothers Edoardo and Dario took a double victory over the film.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Hungarian swordsmen won a triple victory over the preserve.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Modern pentathlon Olympic competitions was held at Ahvenisto Hämeenlinna.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A total of 51 competitors from 19 countries entered the sport.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] For the first time in Olympic history, the sport also included a team competition.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Sweden, Hungary and Finland shared the medals.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Sweden's Lars Hall won the individual competition, and Hungary was the best in the team competition.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Before Hall, all Olympic winners of the sport have been officers.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] However, Hall was a carpenter by profession.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Töölö Sports Hall held Olympic boxing between 28 July to 2 August in ten weight classes.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The most successful boxing country was the United States, which won five gold.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Soviet Union won the most medals, but its boxers did not win a single championship.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the middle series, the American Floyd Patterson knocked out Romanian Vasile Tiță in a record-breaking 42 seconds.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The American Norvel Lee, who won the heavyweight series, was awarded as the most technical boxer in the Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the heavyweight series Ed Sanders got gold when the Swedish Ingemar Johansson was rejected for his passivity.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Johansson did not receive his silver medal until 1982.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Wrestling was held in Helsinki in eight weight classes in both Greco-Roman wrestling and freestyle wrestling.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] All finals were held in the larger Exhibition Hall I, but freestyle wrestling events were held in the smaller Exhibition Hall II.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Free button competitions were held on 20–23 July, and Greco-Roman wrestling matches took place on 24–27 July.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The most successful wrestling country was the Soviet Union, whose athletes won six gold and a total of ten medals in the sport.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Sweden dominated free wrestling and received the second highest number of medals in wrestling overall.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The overwhelming athlete in wrestling was the Soviet Johannes Kotkas, who competed in the heavy series of Greco-Roman wrestling.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] He managed to beat all his opponents in less than five minutes.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Olympic weightlifting competition was held in seven weight classes with 141 competitors.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Initially, there were to be only six weight classes, but a light heavyweight series was also added to the program, as a result of which the weight limit for the heavyweight series increased from 82.5 kilograms to 90 kilograms.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The addition of the new weight class took place so late that there was no time to change the race program.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Weightlifting was carried out according to plan at the Exhibition Hall on 25–27 July.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] All seven gold medals were awarded to athletes from the United States and the Soviet Union.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Soviets won a total of seven medals, but the Americans took four championships, while the Soviets only took three.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A total of five world records were set in weightlifting.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the heavyweight series John Davis continued his superiority, Davis had not lost a single event since 1938 and continued with his victory in Helsinki as well.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The competition took place in the waters of Helsinki from 20 to 28 May in five different categories.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Larger boats sailed in front of Harmaja lighthouse island, and the Finn race was held near Liuskasaari.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A total of 93 crews from 29 countries took part in the competition.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The United States, Norway and Sweden took three medals.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The United States was the only country to reach two gold medals in sailing.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the Finn that developed from the Firefly class, the Danish Paul Elvstrøm won the overwhelming championship.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The gold medal was the second in Elvstrøm's career.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] He later became the first athlete to win the same sport four times in a row (individual disciplines).
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In cycling, medals were awarded in six sports, four for track cycling and two for road racing.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In total, 214 competitors from 36 countries took part in the cycling.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Track cycling competitions were held from 29 to 31 July and road driving on 2 August.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A total of seven countries collected medals and gold medals went to Italy, Australia and Belgium.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Italy was the most successful country with five medals.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Two gold medals went to Australian Russell Mockridge, who won the championship in the kilometer time trial and with his partner in tandem racing, and the Belgian André Noyelle, who won the 190 kilometer road race personal competition and team competition.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Equestrian events were competed in dressage, Eventing and show jumping in person and in team competition in a total of six sports.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Eight countries won medals in horseback riding, and Sweden was by far the most successful country.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Swedes won both races in both dressage and field riding.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] For the events in first time non-military officers including women were allowed to take part in dressage events in Helsinki.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In a show jumping, Danish Lis Hartel, paralyzed from her knees down, was the first woman to win a riding medal after finishing second in the Olympics.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Rowers competed in seven sports from 20 to 23 July.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The competition was held in Meilahti, as Taivallahti, where the canoeing competitions took place, was too open to the sea breeze.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] There were a total of 409 entrants from 33 countries.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Representatives from fourteen countries won medals, and only American rowers won two gold medals.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The youngest Olympic winner of the Games was seen in Rowing.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the coxswain duo, the French winning team included 14 years old Bernard Malivoire.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Diving competed in a total of four men's and women's events.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The United States led the events, as nine of the 12 medals in the distribution went to the country.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In addition to the United States, only France, Mexico and Germany won medals in the sport.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Patricia McCormick won Olympic gold in the women's events from both the three-meter springboard and the ten-meter floor jump.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] At the Helsinki Swimming Stadium men competed in six sports and women in five sports.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] High-level competitions were held from July 25 to 2 August.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Summer Olympics in London had resulted in significant progress in the sport, and every Olympic record was broken in each event.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Americans dominated men's events and the Hungarians dominated women.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Ford Konno was the most successful swimmer with two gold medals and one silver.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the women's events Katalin Szőke won two gold medals and Éva Novák two silver in addition to the gold medal.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The only world record in the Games was set by the Hungarian women's 4 × 100 meter freestyle message team.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Helsinki Olympics, was the last instance where competitors could participate in Breaststroke in the butterfly stroke.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the men's events, no athlete swimming in the breaststroke style made it to the finals.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A total of 21 countries took part in the water polo tournament.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The initial series of the Games was to be played in the offshore pools, but due to the coolness of the water, the International Swimming Federation ordered all the matches to be played at the Swimming Stadium.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Because of this, some of the matches in the first series had to be played as early as six in the morning.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The water polo championship was decided in the final block, where the four teams faced each other once.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Hungary and Yugoslavia ended in a draw after winning two other matches and playing 2–2 each other.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Hungary won gold with a better goal difference.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The 1952 Olympic gymnastics was dominated by the Soviet Union, which had already been an established gymnastics power by 1952.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The USSR's athletes won nine gold medals and took a total of 22 medals.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Finland, Germany and Switzerland, who previously dominated the gymnastics at the Olympics, were content with more modest success.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A total of fifteen medals were awarded, eight in men's events and seven in women's events.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The most personal medals in gymnastics were taken by Viktor Chukarin in the men's events and Maria Gorokhovskaya in the women's events.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Gorokhovskaya won medals in every women's sport.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Her seven-medal catch (two gold and five silver) was a record for one women's Olympics.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Athletics was competed in 33 sports, 24 for men and 9 for women.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] By far the most successful state was the United States, which won 31 medals, nine of which were gold.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Soviet Union reached 17 medals, but won only two championships, and the eight-medal country Germany was left without first places.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The second medalist was Czechoslovakia, with four of the five medals being the brightest.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Emil Zátopek won the 5,000 and 10,000 meters, as well as the marathon, which he had never run before, all in new Olympic record times.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] On the women's side, the Australian Marjorie Jackson won the 100 and 200 meter runs.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the triple jump Adhemar Ferreira da Silva broke the old world record four times.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the decathlon, Bob Mathias made a new ME and took the victory with a total score of 7,887 points, more than 900 points to the next.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Josy Barthel of Luxembourg pulled a major surprise by winning the 1500 m.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] According to the Olympic rules, the organizer of the Games was allowed to choose between two types of demonstration sports, one from abroad and one from Finland.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In connection with the Helsinki Games, a handball and pesäpallo (Finnish baseball) match was held.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the handball match of the Games, Sweden and Denmark faced at the Olympic Stadium.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The level of playing outside was modest due to heavy rain.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The pesäpallo match was also played at the Olympic Stadium.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Finnish Baseball Federation and Finnish Workers' Sports Federation teams competed in the event.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Baseball Federation won the match 8–4.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] During the breaks in both shows, the audience was entertained by the performances of Finnish male and female gymnasts.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] With an annual average temperature of 5.9 °C (42.6 °F), Helsinki is one of the coldest cities to have hosted the Summer Olympics.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Most of the competition venues were located in Helsinki Metropolitan Area.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Modern pentathlon and some field hockey games were held in Hämeenlinna and some football games by Tampere, Lahti, Kotka and Turku.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The main arena was the Olympic Stadium, which hosted the opening and closing ceremonies, athletics competitions, football semi-finals and finals, as well as the show jumping competition "Prix des Nations" were held.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The stadium was built for the 1940 Olympics and opened as early as 1938, but had suffered under the bombing of World War II.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] It had to undergo expansion and refurbishment work.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The concrete auditorium section was expanded and a new temporary wooden auditorium was built on the south and north curves and on the east side, which increased the Stadium's audience capacity to about 70,000.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The swimming competitions were held at Helsinki Swimming Stadium, located just a few hundred meters east of the Olympic Stadium and with three pools: a racing, diving and children's pool.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The swimming stadium could accommodate about 9,500 spectators, while the wooden eastern and standing stands for the Games could accommodate a total of about 6,000 people.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Fair Hall near the stadiums (now Töölö Sports Hall) many of the indoor events were held in two separate halls.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the bigger hall, men competed in gymnastics, wrestling and boxing.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The smaller hall hosts the women's gymnastics, freestyle wrestling, weightlifting and basketball finals.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Basketball first round matches were played at Tennis Palace and fencing competitions were held at the Westend tennis center in Espoo.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The shooting events took place at the Malmi shooting range 11 kilometers from the center of Helsinki, with the exception of clay pigeon shooting.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Clay pigeon shooting was performed on the Finnish Hunters' Association track Huopalahti.Ruskeasuo competed in dressage as well as in Tali and Laakso in field riding.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Töölö Rowing Stadium was built for rowing and canoeing events one kilometer from Taivallahti.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] However, the place was not accepted as a place for rowing competitions, as it was open to the sea breeze.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The rowing took place in Meilahti about three kilometers from the Stadium.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The place was considerably more sheltered than Taivallahti.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Harmaja, a lighthouse island a couple of kilometers off the coast of Helsinki, was the starting and finishing area for larger sailing classes.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Finn was the starting and finish point of the race Liuskasaari close to the coast.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Marathon running route was north of the Stadium to Käpylä, Pakinkylä, Tuomarinkylä, Vantaa, Tikkurila and Korso.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In Tuusula, Mätäkivenmäki there was a turning point from which the runners set off on their way back to the Stadium.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The 50-kilometer walk was organized along the same route.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A memorial stone was later erected at the turning point along Old Tuusulantie.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A swimming stadium was built in Hämeenlinna for Ahvenisto for the pentathlon.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The other four pentathlon events were also held in the vicinity of Ahvenisto.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A total of 69 nations participated in these Games, up from 59 in the 1948 Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Thirteen nations made their first Olympic appearance in 1952: The Bahamas, the People's Republic of China, Gold Coast (now Ghana), Guatemala, Hong Kong, Indonesia, Israel, Netherlands Antilles, Nigeria, the Soviet Union (USSR), Thailand, and Vietnam.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Japan and Germany were both reinstated and permitted to send athletes after being banned for 1948 for their instigation of World War II.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Due to the division of Germany, German athletes from Saar entered a separate team for the only time.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Only West Germany would provide athletes for the actual German team, since East Germany refused to participate in a joint German team.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Romania returned to the games in this edition.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Nations that participated in the previous games in London 1948 but were absent in Helsinki 1952 included Afghanistan, Colombia, Malta, Peru and Syria.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Puerto Rico is an unincorporated territory and commonwealth of the United States.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Bahamas, Bermuda, Gold Coast (modern-day Ghana), Hong Kong, Jamaica, Nigeria, Singapore, Trinidad and Tobago, and British Guyana was all part of the British Empire.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Netherlands Antilles was a constituent country of the Kingdom of Netherlands.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Soviet Union sent the largest delegation.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1952 Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The 50th anniversary of the Helsinki Olympic Games was the main motif for one of the first Finnish euro silver commemorative coins, the €10 silver coin minted in 2002.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The reverse depicts part of the Helsinki Olympic Stadium, as well as a section of the 1952 500 markka coin.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The obverse has lettering SUOMI FINLAND 10 EURO, a flame, and Finland is the only country highlighted on Earth.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] In total 2,394,099 admission tickets were printed for the Helsinki games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] About two million of them were made Bank of Finland banknote printing works.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] To prevent counterfeiting, tickets were printed on watermark banknote paper.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Printing began in July 1951 and lasted four months.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] In early 1952, the race organizers opened their own ticket offices for sales at home and abroad.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Half of the more than two million admission tickets were put up for sale abroad.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] However, only about 250,000 tickets were sold.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] However, foreign tourists also bought a lot of tickets from Finland.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] A total of 1,376,512 tickets were sold for various competition events.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] There were four different price categories.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Prices varied between 300 and 2,100 FIM, which in current currency corresponds to about 9–65 euros.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Ticket revenue totaled approximately FIM 965 million, or EUR 29.7 million.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Entrance tickets were printed in ten different colors, depending on the venue and the auditorium.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Except for the color, the flags were all similar in appearance.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The texts in Finnish, Swedish, English and French were printed on them, and the sport was also indicated by a symbol in the upper left corner.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] A spectator map was printed on the back of the entrance tickets.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Tickets sold to Finland only marked their Price Category, foreign tickets also marked the price US Dollars.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] In addition to tickets made by the organizers, the City of Hämeenlinna printed its own entry tickets for modern pentathlon competitions held locally.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] They were simpler in design than other tickets.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The Olympics influenced the Finns, the City of Helsinki and the image of foreigners.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The Olympics can even be considered a symbolic decision for the post-war years in Finland.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Reconstruction of the land was practically completed in 1952, although at the beginning of the decade many had lived in temporary housing.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The last war reparations was paid in September 1952, and regulatory policy was abolished at the same time.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] On the closing day of the Games, 3 August 1952, President J.K.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Paasikivi wrote in his diary: "The Olympics were a great success.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Foreigners, including the magazines, have praised the good organization.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Helsinki cityscape was clearly a new impetus for the Olympics.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The development of Helsinki had already begun in the late 1930s, when Parliament House, Lasipalatsi and Pääposti were built.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Olympic dreams motivate many construction projects.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Helsinki's entertainment and nightlife was modest compared to previous race hosts.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Many temporary restaurants and entertainment venues were set up in the city for the Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The city had been planning a fair for decades, but even for this project, the Olympic host gave the final impetus.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] After the competition was confirmed, the city of Helsinki started looking for a place for an amusement park in Alppila.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The Linnanmäki Amusement Park was opened on 27 May 1950 on a plot leased in December 1949.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The Olympics also developed Helsinki's infrastructure with the construction of a new airport, Olympic Pier, new asphalt and the city's first traffic lights.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The Olympic spirit was also visible outside the capital region.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] In 1952, Finland's first rest stop for motorists was opened in Lahnajärvi, along the former Highway 1 (current road 110).
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The impact of the Olympics on Finns is difficult to define.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] It was certainly good for Finns' self-confidence to create a successful major event together and at the same time get a new kind of contact with the interaction between peoples.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] For the first time, many Finns were in contact with non-Caucasian foreigners at the Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] At the same time, the Olympics united Finns in their disputes.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] For example, Finnish Workers' Sports Federation and Finnish Sports Federation strong disputes between were on a break during the Olympics, even though they continued even after the Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] With internationalization, new products also arrived in Finland.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The best known of these is Coca-Cola (Coca-Cola arrived in Finland as early as the 1930s through Stockmann).
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] In addition, chewing gum was imported for the first time, and Alko launched new drinks, including Gin Long Drink.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Finland's relations with United Kingdom clearly warmed up thanks to the Olympics.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] This was particularly influenced by the fact that Prince Philip, who came to visit the Games, received a warm welcome in Finland.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] After the Second World War, Britain had been rude to Finland, but the Olympics showed that Finland belonged to the Western world.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] In Finland, the Helsinki Olympics are sometimes called the last real Olympics, when trying to emphasize the nature of the Games as the last Games of the true Olympic spirit, a sporting and non-commercial event.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] For example, a book about competitions written by Antero Raevuori is named after this saying.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] However, the phrase was invented in Finland and is not used elsewhere in the world.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] It was developed at the turn of the 1970s and 1980s, when doping began to become more widespread in sports, 1972 Summer Olympics the Munich massacre, and the 1976, 1980 and 1984 the Summer Olympics were widely boycotted.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] In a way, the Helsinki Olympics were a return to smaller competitions due to resources, as Finland is the smallest country to host the Summer Olympics.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] However the 1956 Summer Olympics involved fewer participating athletes than in Helsinki, and in practice it was not until the 1970s that the Games clearly began to expand.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The Helsinki Olympics were still relatively non-commercial, although the Polish press, for example, barked at the Helsinki Olympics as "competitions for disgusting traders".
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The Helsinki Games were also not much smaller in terms of marketing than the following Games, and marketing was well known in the Olympic world with Kodak supporting the Games as far back as the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] The Soviet Union won the most gold and overall medals at these Games.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] These Games were the first to be staged in the Southern Hemisphere and Oceania, as well as the first to be held outside Europe and North America.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Melbourne is the most southerly city ever to host the Olympics.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Australia hosted the Games for a second time in 2000 in Sydney, New South Wales, and will host them again in 2032 in Brisbane, Queensland.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] The Olympic equestrian events could not be held in Melbourne due to Australia's strict quarantine regulations, so they were held in Stockholm five months earlier.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] This was the second time the Olympics were not held entirely in one country, the first being the 1920 Summer Olympics in Antwerp, Belgium, with some events taking place in Amsterdam, Netherlands.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Despite uncertainties and various complications encountered during the preparations, the 1956 Games went ahead in Melbourne as planned and turned out to be a success.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Started during the 1956 Games was the "Parade of Athletes" at the closing ceremonies.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Nine teams boycotted the Games for various reasons.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Four teams (Egypt, Iraq, Cambodia and Lebanon) boycotted in response to the Suez Crisis, in which Egypt was invaded by Israel, France and the United Kingdom.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Four teams (the Netherlands, Spain, Liechtenstein and Switzerland) boycotted in response to the Soviet invasion of Hungary, and the People's Republic of China's boycott was in response to a dispute with the Republic of China over the right to represent China.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] One of the most notable events of the games was a controversial water polo match between the Soviet Union and the defending champions, Hungary.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] The Soviet Union had recently suppressed an anti-authoritarian revolution in Hungary and violence broke out between the teams during the match, resulting in numerous injuries.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] When Hungary's Ervin Zádor suffered bleeding after being punched by the Soviet Union's Valentin Prokopov, spectators attempted to join the violence, but they were blocked by police.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] The match was cancelled, with Hungary being declared the winner because they were in the lead 4–0.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Melbourne was selected as the host city over bids from Buenos Aires, Mexico City, Montreal, Los Angeles, Detroit, Chicago, Minneapolis, Philadelphia, and San Francisco at the 43rd IOC Session in Rome, Italy on 28 April 1949.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Mexico City, Montreal and Los Angeles would eventually be selected to host the 1968, 1976 and 1984 Summer Olympics respectively.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Many members of the IOC were skeptical about Melbourne as an appropriate site.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Its location in the Southern Hemisphere was a major concern since the reversal of seasons would mean the Games must be held during the northern winter.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] The November–December schedule was thought likely to inconvenience athletes from the Northern Hemisphere, who were accustomed to resting during their winter.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Notwithstanding these concerns, the field of candidates eventually narrowed to two Southern Hemisphere cities, these being Melbourne and Buenos Aires, Argentina.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Melbourne was selected, in 1949, to host the 1956 Olympics by a one-vote margin.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] The first sign of trouble was the revelation that Australian equine quarantine would prevent the country from hosting the equestrian events.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Stockholm was selected as the alternative site, so equestrian competition began on 10 June, five and a half months before the rest of the Olympic Games were to open.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] The above problems of the Melbourne Games were compounded by bickering over financing among Australian politicians.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Eventually, in March 1953, the State Government accepted a £2 million loan from the Commonwealth Government to build the Olympic Village, which would accommodate up to 6,000 people, in Heidelberg West.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] After the Olympics, the houses in the village were handed back to the Housing Commission for general public housing.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] At one point, IOC President Avery Brundage suggested that Rome, which was to host the 1960 Games, was so far ahead of Melbourne in preparations that it might be ready as a replacement site in 1956.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Constructing of the sporting venues was given priority over the athlete's village.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] The village was designed as a whole new suburb with semi-detached houses and flats, the first village that both sexes could cohabitate the same buildings instead of gender designated sections.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] As late as April 1955, Brundage, who was presiding over the Olympics for the first time, was still doubtful about Melbourne and was not satisfied by an inspection trip to the city.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Construction was well under way by then, thanks to a $4.5 million federal loan to Victoria, but it was behind schedule.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] He still held out the possibility that Rome might have to step in.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] By the beginning of 1956, though, it was obvious that Melbourne would be ready for the Olympics.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Egypt, Iraq, Cambodia and Lebanon announced that they would not participate in the Olympics in response to the Suez Crisis when Egypt was invaded by Israel, the United Kingdom, and France.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] The Netherlands, Spain, Switzerland and Liechtenstein boycotted the event in protest of the Soviet Union's crushing of the Hungarian Revolution.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] The People's Republic of China chose to boycott the event because Taiwan had been allowed to compete.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Athletes from both East and West Germany competed together as a combined team (a display of unity that was repeated in 1960 and 1964, but was then discontinued).
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Although the number of countries participating (67) was almost the same as in 1952 (69), the number of athletes competing dropped sharply, from 4,925 to 3,342.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Once underway, the Games progressed smoothly, and came to be known as the "Friendly Games".
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Betty Cuthbert, an 18-year-old from Sydney, won the 100 and 200 metre sprint races and ran an exceptional final leg in the 4 x 100 metre relay to overcome Great Britain's lead and claim her third gold medal, becoming known as the "Golden Girl".
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] The veteran Shirley Strickland repeated her 1952 win in the 80 metre hurdles and was also part of the winning 4 x 100 metre relay team, bringing her career Olympic medal total to seven: three golds, a silver, and three bronze medals.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] They won all of the freestyle races, men's and women's, and collected a total of eight gold, four silver and two bronze medals.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Murray Rose became the first male swimmer to win two freestyle events (and a total three events) since Johnny Weissmuller in 1924, while Dawn Fraser won gold medals in the 100 metre freestyle and as the leadoff swimmer in the 4 x 100 metre relay team.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] The men's track and field events were dominated by the United States.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] They not only won 15 of the 24 events, they swept four of them and took first and second place in five others.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Bobby Morrow led the way with gold medals in the 100 and 200 metre sprints and the 4 x 100 metre relay.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Tom Courtney barely overtook Great Britain's Derek Johnson in the 800 metre run, then collapsed from the exertion and needed medical attention.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Ireland's Ronnie Delany ran an outstanding 53.8 over the last 400 metres to win the 1,500 metre run (also Ireland's last gold medal in track events), in which favourite John Landy of Australia finished third.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] There was a major upset, marred briefly by controversy, in the 3,000 metre steeplechase.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Little-known Chris Brasher of Great Britain finished well ahead of the field, but the judges disqualified him for interfering with Norway's Ernst Larsen, and they announced Sándor Rozsnyói of Hungary as the winner.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Brasher's appeal was supported by Larsen, Rozsnyói, and fourth-place finisher Heinz Laufer of Germany.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Subsequently, the decision was reversed and Brasher became the first Briton to win a gold medal in track and field since 1936.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Soviet runner Vladimir Kuts won two golds by winning both the 5,000-metre and 10,000-metre events.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Only two world records were set in track and field.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Mildred McDaniel, the first American woman to win gold in the sport, set a high jump record of 1.76 metres (5.8 ft), and Egil Danielsen of Norway overcame blustery conditions with a remarkable javelin throw of 85.71 metres (281.2 ft).
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Throughout the Olympics, Hungarian athletes were cheered by fans from Australia and other countries.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Many of them gathered in the boxing arena when thirty-year-old Laszlo Papp of Hungary won a record third gold medal by beating José Torres for the light-middleweight championship.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] A few days later, the crowd was with the Hungarian water polo team in its hotly contested and emotionally charged match against the Soviet Union which took place against the background of the Soviet invasion of Hungary.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] The game became rough and, when a Hungarian was forced to leave the pool with a bleeding wound above his eye, a riot almost broke out.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] The police restored order and the game was called early, with Hungary leading 4–0, and the Hungarians went on to win the gold medal.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] In a much publicized Olympic romance, American hammer throw champion Hal Connolly would marry Czechoslovak discus throw champion, Olga Fikotová.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] After moving to the United States, Olga wanted to continue representing Czechoslovakia, but the Czechoslovak Olympic Committee would not allow her to do so.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Thereafter, as Olga Connolly, she took part in every Olympics until 1972 competing for the U.S.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] She was the flag bearer for the U.S. team at the 1972 Summer Olympics.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] The India men's national field hockey team won its sixth consecutive Olympic gold.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Despite the international tensions of 1956—or perhaps because of them—a young Melburnian, John Ian Wing, came up with a new idea for the closing ceremony.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Instead of marching as separate teams, behind their national flags, the athletes mingled together as they paraded into and around the arena for a final appearance before the spectators.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] It was the start of an Olympic tradition that has been followed ever since.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] The Olympic flame was relayed to Melbourne after being lit at Olympia on 2 November 1956.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Greek runners took the flame from Olympia to Athens.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] The flame was then transferred to a miner's lamp, flown by a Qantas Super Constellation aircraft, "Southern Horizon" to Darwin, Northern Territory.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] A Royal Australian Air Force English Electric Canberra jet bomber transported the flame to Cairns, Queensland, where it arrived on 9 November 1956 and the Mayor of Cairns, Alderman W.J.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Fulton, lit the first torch with the torch design was identical to the one used for the 1948 London Games (except for the engraved city name and year).
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] The first runner was Con Verevis, a local man of Greek parentage.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] The flame was relayed down the east coast of Australia using die cast aluminium torches weighing about 3 pounds (1.8 kg).
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] The flame arrived in Melbourne on 22 November 1956, the day of the opening ceremony and The flame was lit at the Olympic stadium by Ron Clarke, who accidentally burned his arm in the process.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] While the Olympic flame was being carried to Sydney, an Australian veterinary student named Barry Larkin carried a fake Olympic Flame and fooled the mayor of Sydney.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] The Melbourne Olympic Arts Festival was an arts festival held in conjunction with the Olympics.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] The Olympics were first televised during the 1936 games to a domestic audience in Berlin.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] The 1956 Winter Olympics in Cortina d'Ampezzo were broadcast internationally with the organising committee giving the television rights gratis.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] While there was much interest in the games overseas, no international television or newsreel rights were awarded, as the Melbourne organising committee requested licensing payments for the broadcasting rights.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] However, domestic rights to the games were hastily agreed by the then three Melbourne stations, GTV9, HSV7 and ABV2, only a week before the opening ceremony.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] The three Sydney stations, TCN9, ATN7 and ABN2, syndicated the Melbourne coverage.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Television in Australia was new, having its beginnings in September 1956.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] For many Australians, their first glimpse of television were Olympic broadcasts.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Around five thousand television sets were in Australia by the time of the Games, so the domestic audience largely watched the games at community halls and at Ampol petrol stations.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] The 1956 Summer Olympics featured 17 different sports encompassing 23 disciplines, and medals were awarded in 151 events (145 events in Melbourne and 6 equestrian events in Stockholm).
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] In the list below, the number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] A total of 67 nations competed in the 1956 Olympics.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Eight countries made their Olympic debuts: Cambodia (only competed in the equestrian events in Stockholm), Ethiopia, Fiji, Kenya, Liberia, Malaya, North Borneo (modern-day Sabah of Malaysia), and Uganda.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Athletes from East Germany and West Germany competed together as the United Team of Germany, an arrangement that would last until 1968.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] For the first time, the team of Republic of China effectively represented only Taiwan.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Five nations competed in the equestrian events in Stockholm, but did not attend the Games in Melbourne.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Cambodia, Egypt and Lebanon did not compete in Melbourne due to a boycott regarding the Suez Crisis, whilst the Netherlands, Spain and Switzerland all boycotted the Melbourne Olympics in protest at the Soviet invasion of Hungary.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Nations that returned to the games in this edition included Afghanistan and Colombia.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Nations that participated in the previous games in Helsinki 1952 but was absent in Melbourne 1956 included the People's Republic of China, Liechtenstein, Netherlands Antilles, and Saar.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] Bahamas, Bermuda, Fiji, Gold Coast (modern-day Ghana), Hong Kong, Jamaica, Kenya, Nigeria, Malaya, North Borneo, Singapore, Trinidad and Tobago, Uganda and British Guyana was all part of the British Empire.
[src:100-meter-running-deer/1956-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1956 Games.
